{"title_page": "Miyake-jima", "text_new": "{{Infobox islands\n| name             = Miyakejima\n| image_name       = 20140516\u4e09\u5b85\u5cf6.jpg\n| image_caption    = \n| image_size       = \n| locator_map      = \n| native_name      = \u4e09\u5b85\u5cf6\n| native_name_link = \n| nickname         = \n| location         = [[Philippine Sea]]\n| coordinates      = {{coord|34.079|139.529|type:isle_region:JP}}\n| archipelago      = [[Izu Islands]]\n| total_islands    = \n| major_islands    = \n| area_km2         = 55.44\n| length_km        = \n| width_km         = \n| coastline_km     = 38.3\n| highest_mount    = Oyama \n| elevation_m      = 775.1\n| country          = Japan\n| country_admin_divisions_title     = [[Prefectures of Japan|Prefecture]]\n| country_admin_divisions           = [[Tokyo]]\n| country_admin_divisions_title_1   = [[Subprefectures of Japan|Subprefecture]]\n| country_admin_divisions_1         = [[Miyake Subprefecture]]\n| country_admin_divisions_title_2   = [[Villages of Japan|Village]]\n| country_admin_divisions_2         = [[Miyake, Tokyo|Miyake]]\n| country_leader_name               = \n| population       = 2,460\n| population_as_of = 2019\n| density_km2      = 44.37\n| ethnic_groups    = Japanese\n| additional_info  =\n}}\n\n{{Nihongo|'''Miyake-jima'''|\u4e09\u5b85\u5cf6|extra=\"Miyake Island\"}} is an inhabited volcanic island in the [[Izu Islands|Izu archipelago]] in the [[Philippine Sea]] approximately {{convert|180|km|mi|sp=us}} southeast of [[Tokyo]], [[Japan]].<ref>[[Louis-Fr\u00e9d\u00e9ric|Nussbaum, Louis-Fr\u00e9d\u00e9ric]]. (2005). [https://books.google.com/books?id=p2QnPijAEmEC&pg=PA412&dq= \"''Izu Shot\u014d'',\"] ''Japan Encyclopedia,'' p. 412.</ref>  As with the other islands in the Izu Island group, Miyake-jima forms part of the [[Fuji-Hakone-Izu National Park]].\n\n==Geography==\n[[File:Miyake-jima-map.jpg|thumb|left|Map of Miyake-jima,<br/>with [[\u014cnoharajima]] west south-west of it]]\nThe island is a [[stratovolcano]] with a [[granite|granitic]] composite cone, dating from the late [[Pleistocene]] period, between 10,000 and 15,000 years ago. The island has a roughly circular coastline, 38.3 kilometers in length, with an average diameter of eight kilometers. The highest elevation {{nihongo|Mount Oyama|\u96c4\u5c71|Oyama-san}} is an active volcano with a height of 775.1 meters. The mountain has been recorded to have erupted numerous times throughout history, and is mentioned as far back as [[Nara period]] written records. Over the past 500 years, it has erupted 13 times, including five times since the start of the [[Meiji period]]. A lava flow in 1940 killed 11&nbsp;people, and other eruptions occurred in 1962 and 1983.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://volcano.und.nodak.edu/vwdocs/volc_images/north_asia/miyakejima/oyama.html |title=Archived copy |accessdate=2005-02-03 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20050222084014/http://volcano.und.nodak.edu/vwdocs/volc_images/north_asia/miyakejima/oyama.html |archivedate=2005-02-22 }}</ref>\nOn July 14, 2000, Mount Oyama began another series of eruptions, and by September, the island was completely evacuated.  After a four-year period of volcanic emissions, residents were allowed to return permanently on February 1, 2005. After the eruption, there has been a constant flow of [[sulfur dioxide]] gas coming from Mount Oyama.\nThe residents of the island are required to carry [[gas mask]]s with them at all times{{citation needed|date=January 2020}}, but they do not need to be worn constantly. Alarms go off if there is a dramatic increase in the levels of toxic gases in the air.<ref>{{Cite web |url=http://www.jnto.go.jp/eng/indepth/featuredarticles/JN/miyake_fishing/miyake_fishing.pdf |title=International Surf Angling Festival for Miyakejima Island Reconstruction, November 4, 2006 |access-date=January 10, 2011 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20110626222608/http://www.jnto.go.jp/eng/indepth/featuredarticles/JN/miyake_fishing/miyake_fishing.pdf |archive-date=June 26, 2011 |url-status=bot: unknown }}</ref>{{Obsolete source|date=January 2020}} Volcanic gas emissions from this volcano are measured by a [[Multi-Component Gas Analyzer System]], which detects pre-eruptive degassing of rising magmas, improving [[prediction of volcanic activity]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://meetingorganizer.copernicus.org/EGU2009/EGU2009-5839.pdf|title=Real-Time Multi-GAS sensing of volcanic gas composition: experiences from the permanent Etna and Stromboli networks, Geophysical Research Abstracts, Vol. 11, EGU2009-5839}}</ref>\n\n==Climate==\nMiyake-jima has a [[humid subtropical climate]] ([[K\u00f6ppen climate classification]] ''Cfa'') with very warm summers and mild winters. Precipitation is abundant throughout the year, but is somewhat lower in winter.\n\n{{Weather box|width=auto\n|location = Miyake-jima\n|single line = Y\n|metric first = Y\n|Jan high C = 11.6\n|Feb high C = 11.5\n|Mar high C = 13.8\n|Apr high C = 18.1\n|May high C = 21.4\n|Jun high C = 24.0\n|Jul high C = 27.1\n|Aug high C = 28.5\n|Sep high C = 26.2\n|Oct high C = 22.2\n|Nov high C = 18.6\n|Dec high C = 14.2\n|Jan mean C = 9.5\n|Feb mean C = 9.2\n|Mar mean C = 11.3\n|Apr mean C = 15.4\n|May mean C = 18.8\n|Jun mean C = 21.6\n|Jul mean C = 24.8\n|Aug mean C = 26.1\n|Sep mean C = 24.0\n|Oct mean C = 19.9\n|Nov mean C = 16.3\n|Dec mean C = 12.1\n|Jan low C = 6.8\n|Feb low C = 6.4\n|Mar low C = 8.4\n|Apr low C = 12.4\n|May low C = 15.9\n|Jun low C = 19.2\n|Jul low C = 22.6\n|Aug low C = 23.9\n|Sep low C = 21.7\n|Oct low C = 17.4\n|Nov low C = 13.5\n|Dec low C = 9.2\n|precipitation colour = green\n|Jan precipitation mm = 138.3\n|Feb precipitation mm = 172.9\n|Mar precipitation mm = 248.8\n|Apr precipitation mm = 239.2\n|May precipitation mm = 250.4\n|Jun precipitation mm = 328.2\n|Jul precipitation mm = 196.0\n|Aug precipitation mm = 225.9\n|Sep precipitation mm = 323.6\n|Oct precipitation mm = 352.4\n|Nov precipitation mm = 255.6\n|Dec precipitation mm = 140.7\n|Jan humidity = 63\n|Feb humidity = 65\n|Mar humidity = 68\n|Apr humidity = 74\n|May humidity = 77\n|Jun humidity = 84\n|Jul humidity = 86\n|Aug humidity = 85\n|Sep humidity = 82\n|Oct humidity = 75\n|Nov humidity = 70\n|Dec humidity = 65\n|Jan sun = 124.1\n|Feb sun = 113.0\n|Mar sun = 138.2\n|Apr sun = 150.5\n|May sun = 176.8\n|Jun sun = 131.6\n|Jul sun = 179.2\n|Aug sun = 211.0\n|Sep sun = 142.8\n|Oct sun = 109.6\n|Nov sun = 103.5\n|Dec sun = 125.6\n|source 1 = NOAA (1961-1990)<ref name= NOAA>{{cite web\n  |url = ftp://ftp.atdd.noaa.gov/pub/GCOS/WMO-Normals/RA-II/JP/47677.TXT\n  |title = Miyakejima Climate Normals 1961-1990\n  |publisher = [[National Oceanic and Atmospheric Administration]]\n  |accessdate = January 5, 2013}}</ref> \n|date=January 2013}}\n\n==Administration==\nThe island is administered by the Miyake subprefecture of the [[Tokyo Metropolis|Tokyo Metropolitan]] government.  As of June 1, 2016, the population of the island was 2451. {{nihongo|[[Miyake, Tokyo|Miyake Village]]|\u4e09\u5b85\u6751|Miyake-mura}} serves as the local government of the island, and also encloses nearby tiny uninhabited [[\u014cnoharajima]] west south-west of Miyake-jima. \n\nMiyake village consists of the five traditional hamlets of Izu, Kamitsuki, Igaya, Ako and Tsubota, with Tsubota on the southeast coast as the administrative center.\n\n==Flora and fauna==\nMiyake-jima is home to the rare endemic [[Izu thrush]] (''akakokko'').<ref>[http://www.asahi.com/english/vox/TKY200502030145.html asahi.com : English<!-- Bot generated title -->]</ref>\nThe island is home to an unusually rich flora and fauna with several rare species of birds and animals, although its natural habitats are constantly under threat from human and volcanic activity. \nUnderwater, the island is valued by divers for its coral reefs and marine fauna (including the dolphin population outside nearby [[Mikura-jima]]).\n\n==Access==\nThe island is accessible by over-night ferry, the ''Sarubia Maru'' or the ''Tachibana Maru'', which is operated by T\u014dkai Kisen. The ferry departs from [[Takeshiba Pier]], near [[Hamamatsuch\u014d Station]], Tokyo at 22:30 and arrives at Miyakejima at 5:00. Depending on the wind and weather conditions, the ''Tachibana Maru'' will dock at one of three ports; Miike Port Pier (\u4e09\u6c60\u6e2f\u685f\u6a4b), T\u014dkai Kisen Igaya Port (\u6771\u6d77\u6c7d\u8239 \u4f0a\u30f6\u8c37), or Sabigahama Port (\u9306\u30f6\u6d5c\u6e2f). The port where the boat will dock is not predictable and changes on a daily basis. Generally, the boat will arrive at the port that is complimentary with the wind direction.<ref>https://www.tokaikisen.co.jp/en/</ref>  \n\nThere are flights connecting [[Miyakejima Airport]] and [[Haneda Airport]] with an approximate flying time of 50&nbsp;minutes. Flights are also operated from [[Chofu Airport]]. The area is prone to high volume of sulfuric gas and flights were suspended for almost eight years after the July 14, 2000 volcano eruption. Flights resumed during April 2008, after sulfuric gases in the air dropped to levels below 0.2ppm.<ref>[https://archive.is/20080426162442/http://www.yomiuri.co.jp/national/news/20080426-OYT1T00501.htm] </ref> There is a helicopter that arrives via [[Izu \u014cshima]]. There are also two helicopter flights operated by Tokyo Island Shuttle which originate in [[Aogashima]] and [[Izu \u014cshima]] and fly to [[Toshima Island|Toshima]], Miyake-jima, [[Mikura-jima]], [[Hachij\u014d-jima]] and [[Aogashima]].\n\nThere are two bus routes on the island. Both bus routes service the same stops, but one route goes clockwise and the other route goes counter-clockwise around the island. The time between each bus stop arrival can vary greatly from a few minutes to up to 3 hours.<ref>https://www.miyakejima.gr.jp/wp/wp-content/uploads/2018/04/basjikokuhyou20180501.pdf</ref>\n[[File:Miyake-jima Bus Stop.jpg|thumb|Typical bus stop with Izu Thrush bus marker]]\n\n==See also==\n{{Portal|Tokyo|Islands}}\n* [[List of volcanoes in Japan]]\n* [[List of islands of Japan]]\n* [[Izu Islands]]\n* [[Devil's Sea]]\n* [[Jack Moyer]] (1929-2004), former resident and marine biologist\n*[[Two Car]] (2017), an animated television series set in Miyake-jima\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n* ''Teikoku's Complete Atlas of Japan'', Teikoku-Shoin., Ltd. Tokyo 1990, {{ISBN|4-8071-0004-1}}\n\n==External links==\n{{Commons category|Miyakejima}}\n{{Wikivoyage|Miyakejima}}\n* [http://www.miyakemura.com/ Miyake Village Official Website]\n* [http://www.data.jma.go.jp/svd/vois/data/tokyo/320_Miyakejima/320_index.html Miyakejima] - Japan Meteorological Agency {{in lang|ja}}\n* {{cite web|url= http://www.data.jma.go.jp/svd/vois/data/tokyo/STOCK/souran_eng/volcanoes/062_miyakejima.pdf |title=Miyakejima: National catalogue of the active volcanoes in Japan }} - Japan Meteorological Agency\n* [https://gbank.gsj.jp/volcano/Quat_Vol/volcano_data/G07.html Miyake Jima] - Geological Survey of Japan\n* [http://volcano.si.edu/volcano.cfm?vn=284040 Miyakejima: Global Volcanism Program] - Smithsonian Institution\n\n{{Authority control}}\n\n[[Category:Izu Islands]]\n[[Category:Stratovolcanoes of Japan]]\n[[Category:Active volcanoes]]\n[[Category:Islands of Tokyo]]\n[[Category:Volcanoes of Tokyo]]\n", "text_old": "{{Infobox islands\n| name             = Miyakejima\n| image_name       = 20140516\u4e09\u5b85\u5cf6.jpg\n| image_caption    = \n| image_size       = \n| locator_map      = \n| native_name      = \u4e09\u5b85\u5cf6\n| native_name_link = \n| nickname         = \n| location         = [[Philippine Sea]]\n| coordinates      = {{coord|34.079|139.529|type:isle_region:JP}}\n| archipelago      = [[Izu Islands]]\n| total_islands    = \n| major_islands    = \n| area_km2         = 55.44\n| length_km        = \n| width_km         = \n| coastline_km     = 38.3\n| highest_mount    = Oyama \n| elevation_m      = 775.1\n| country          = Japan\n| country_admin_divisions_title     = [[Prefectures of Japan|Prefecture]]\n| country_admin_divisions           = [[Tokyo]]\n| country_admin_divisions_title_1   = [[Subprefectures of Japan|Subprefecture]]\n| country_admin_divisions_1         = [[Miyake Subprefecture]]\n| country_admin_divisions_title_2   = [[Villages of Japan|Village]]\n| country_admin_divisions_2         = [[Miyake, Tokyo|Miyake]]\n| country_leader_name               = \n| population       = 2,460\n| population_as_of = 2019\n| density_km2      = 44.37\n| ethnic_groups    = Japanese\n| additional_info  =\n}}\n\n{{Nihongo|'''Miyake-jima'''|\u4e09\u5b85\u5cf6|extra=\"Miyake Island\"}} is an inhabited volcanic island in the [[Izu Islands|Izu archipelago]] in the [[Philippine Sea]] approximately {{convert|180|km|mi|sp=us}} southeast of [[Tokyo]], [[Japan]].<ref>[[Louis-Fr\u00e9d\u00e9ric|Nussbaum, Louis-Fr\u00e9d\u00e9ric]]. (2005). [https://books.google.com/books?id=p2QnPijAEmEC&pg=PA412&dq= \"''Izu Shot\u014d'',\"] ''Japan Encyclopedia,'' p. 412.</ref>  As with the other islands in the Izu Island group, Miyake-jima forms part of the [[Fuji-Hakone-Izu National Park]].\n\n==Geography==\n[[File:Miyake-jima-map.jpg|thumb|left|Map of Miyake-jima,<br/>with [[\u014cnoharajima]] west south-west of it]]\nThe island is a [[stratovolcano]] with a [[granite|granitic]] composite cone, dating from the late [[Pleistocene]] period, between 10,000 and 15,000 years ago. The island has a roughly circular coastline, 38.3 kilometers in length, with an average diameter of eight kilometers. The highest elevation {{nihongo|Mount Oyama|\u96c4\u5c71|Oyama-san}} is an active volcano with a height of 775.1 meters. The mountain has been recorded to have erupted numerous times throughout history, and is mentioned as far back as [[Nara period]] written records. Over the past 500 years, it has erupted 13 times, including five times since the start of the [[Meiji period]]. A lava flow in 1940 killed 11&nbsp;people, and other eruptions occurred in 1962 and 1983.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://volcano.und.nodak.edu/vwdocs/volc_images/north_asia/miyakejima/oyama.html |title=Archived copy |accessdate=2005-02-03 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20050222084014/http://volcano.und.nodak.edu/vwdocs/volc_images/north_asia/miyakejima/oyama.html |archivedate=2005-02-22 }}</ref>\nOn July 14, 2000, Mount Oyama began another series of eruptions, and by September, the island was completely evacuated.  After a four-year period of volcanic emissions, residents were allowed to return permanently on February 1, 2005. After the eruption, there has been a constant flow of [[sulfur dioxide]] gas coming from Mount Oyama.\nThe residents of the island are required to carry [[gas mask]]s with them at all times{{citation needed|date=January 2020}}, but they do not need to be worn constantly. Alarms go off if there is a dramatic increase in the levels of toxic gases in the air.<ref>{{Cite web |url=http://www.jnto.go.jp/eng/indepth/featuredarticles/JN/miyake_fishing/miyake_fishing.pdf |title=International Surf Angling Festival for Miyakejima Island Reconstruction, November 4, 2006 |access-date=January 10, 2011 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20110626222608/http://www.jnto.go.jp/eng/indepth/featuredarticles/JN/miyake_fishing/miyake_fishing.pdf |archive-date=June 26, 2011 |url-status=bot: unknown }}</ref>{{Obsolete source|date=January 2020}} Volcanic gas emissions from this volcano are measured by a [[Multi-Component Gas Analyzer System]], which detects pre-eruptive degassing of rising magmas, improving [[prediction of volcanic activity]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://meetingorganizer.copernicus.org/EGU2009/EGU2009-5839.pdf|title=Real-Time Multi-GAS sensing of volcanic gas composition: experiences from the permanent Etna and Stromboli networks, Geophysical Research Abstracts, Vol. 11, EGU2009-5839}}</ref>\n\n==Climate==\nMiyake-jima has a [[humid subtropical climate]] ([[K\u00f6ppen climate classification]] ''Cfa'') with very warm summers and mild winters. Precipitation is abundant throughout the year, but is somewhat lower in winter.\n\n{{Weather box|width=auto\n|location = Miyake-jima\n|single line = Y\n|metric first = Y\n|Jan high C = 11.6\n|Feb high C = 11.5\n|Mar high C = 13.8\n|Apr high C = 18.1\n|May high C = 21.4\n|Jun high C = 24.0\n|Jul high C = 27.1\n|Aug high C = 28.5\n|Sep high C = 26.2\n|Oct high C = 22.2\n|Nov high C = 18.6\n|Dec high C = 14.2\n|Jan mean C = 9.5\n|Feb mean C = 9.2\n|Mar mean C = 11.3\n|Apr mean C = 15.4\n|May mean C = 18.8\n|Jun mean C = 21.6\n|Jul mean C = 24.8\n|Aug mean C = 26.1\n|Sep mean C = 24.0\n|Oct mean C = 19.9\n|Nov mean C = 16.3\n|Dec mean C = 12.1\n|Jan low C = 6.8\n|Feb low C = 6.4\n|Mar low C = 8.4\n|Apr low C = 12.4\n|May low C = 15.9\n|Jun low C = 19.2\n|Jul low C = 22.6\n|Aug low C = 23.9\n|Sep low C = 21.7\n|Oct low C = 17.4\n|Nov low C = 13.5\n|Dec low C = 9.2\n|precipitation colour = green\n|Jan precipitation mm = 138.3\n|Feb precipitation mm = 172.9\n|Mar precipitation mm = 248.8\n|Apr precipitation mm = 239.2\n|May precipitation mm = 250.4\n|Jun precipitation mm = 328.2\n|Jul precipitation mm = 196.0\n|Aug precipitation mm = 225.9\n|Sep precipitation mm = 323.6\n|Oct precipitation mm = 352.4\n|Nov precipitation mm = 255.6\n|Dec precipitation mm = 140.7\n|Jan humidity = 63\n|Feb humidity = 65\n|Mar humidity = 68\n|Apr humidity = 74\n|May humidity = 77\n|Jun humidity = 84\n|Jul humidity = 86\n|Aug humidity = 85\n|Sep humidity = 82\n|Oct humidity = 75\n|Nov humidity = 70\n|Dec humidity = 65\n|Jan sun = 124.1\n|Feb sun = 113.0\n|Mar sun = 138.2\n|Apr sun = 150.5\n|May sun = 176.8\n|Jun sun = 131.6\n|Jul sun = 179.2\n|Aug sun = 211.0\n|Sep sun = 142.8\n|Oct sun = 109.6\n|Nov sun = 103.5\n|Dec sun = 125.6\n|source 1 = NOAA (1961-1990)<ref name= NOAA>{{cite web\n  |url = ftp://ftp.atdd.noaa.gov/pub/GCOS/WMO-Normals/RA-II/JP/47677.TXT\n  |title = Miyakejima Climate Normals 1961-1990\n  |publisher = [[National Oceanic and Atmospheric Administration]]\n  |accessdate = January 5, 2013}}</ref> \n|date=January 2013}}\n\n==Administration==\nThe island is administered by the Miyake subprefecture of the [[Tokyo Metropolis|Tokyo Metropolitan]] government.  As of June 1, 2016, the population of the island was 2451. {{nihongo|[[Miyake, Tokyo|Miyake Village]]|\u4e09\u5b85\u6751|Miyake-mura}} serves as the local government of the island, and also encloses nearby tiny uninhabited [[\u014cnoharajima]] west south-west of Miyake-jima. \n\nMiyake village consists of the five traditional hamlets of Izu, Kamitsuki, Igaya, Ako and Tsubota, with Tsubota on the southeast coast as the administrative center.\n\n==Flora and fauna==\nMiyake-jima is home to the rare endemic [[Izu thrush]] (''akakokko'').<ref>[http://www.asahi.com/english/vox/TKY200502030145.html asahi.com : English<!-- Bot generated title -->]</ref>\nThe island is home to an unusually rich flora and fauna with several rare species of birds and animals, although its natural habitats are constantly under threat from human and volcanic activity. \nUnderwater, the island is valued by divers for its coral reefs and marine fauna (including the dolphin population outside nearby [[Mikura-jima]]).\n\n==Access==\nThe island is accessible by over-night ferry, the ''Sarubia Maru'' or the ''Tachibana Maru'', which is operated by T\u014dkai Kisen. The ferry departs from [[Takeshiba Pier]], near [[Hamamatsuch\u014d Station]], Tokyo at 22:30 and arrives at Miyakejima at 5:00. Depending on the wind and weather conditions, the ''Tachibana Maru'' will dock at one of three ports; Miike Port Pier (\u4e09\u6c60\u6e2f\u685f\u6a4b), T\u014dkai Kisen Igaya Port (\u6771\u6d77\u6c7d\u8239 \u4f0a\u30f6\u8c37), or Sabigahama Port (\u9306\u30f6\u6d5c\u6e2f). The port where the boat will dock is not predictable and changes on a daily basis. Generally, the boat will arrive at the port that is complimentary with the wind direction.<ref>https://www.tokaikisen.co.jp/en/</ref>  \n\nThere are flights connecting [[Miyakejima Airport]] and [[Haneda Airport]] with an approximate flying time of 50&nbsp;minutes. Flights are also operated from [[Chofu Airport]]. The area is prone to high volume of sulfuric gas and flights were suspended for almost eight years after the July 14, 2000 volcano eruption. Flights resumed during April 2008, after sulfuric gases in the air dropped to levels below 0.2ppm.<ref>[https://archive.is/20080426162442/http://www.yomiuri.co.jp/national/news/20080426-OYT1T00501.htm] </ref> There is a helicopter that arrives via [[Izu \u014cshima]]. There are also two helicopter flights operated by Tokyo Island Shuttle which originate in [[Aogashima]] and [[Izu \u014cshima]] and fly to [[Toshima Island|Toshima]], Miyake-jima, [[Mikura-jima]], [[Hachij\u014d-jima]] and [[Aogashima]].\n\nThere are two bus routes on the island. Both bus routes service the same stops, but one route goes clockwise and the other route goes counter-clockwise around the island. The time between each bus stop arrival can vary greatly from a few minutes to up to 3 hours.<ref>https://www.miyakejima.gr.jp/wp/wp-content/uploads/2018/04/basjikokuhyou20180501.pdf</ref>\n\n==See also==\n{{Portal|Tokyo|Islands}}\n* [[List of volcanoes in Japan]]\n* [[List of islands of Japan]]\n* [[Izu Islands]]\n* [[Devil's Sea]]\n* [[Jack Moyer]] (1929-2004), former resident and marine biologist\n*[[Two Car]] (2017), an animated television series set in Miyake-jima\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n* ''Teikoku's Complete Atlas of Japan'', Teikoku-Shoin., Ltd. Tokyo 1990, {{ISBN|4-8071-0004-1}}\n\n==External links==\n{{Commons category|Miyakejima}}\n{{Wikivoyage|Miyakejima}}\n* [http://www.miyakemura.com/ Miyake Village Official Website]\n* [http://www.data.jma.go.jp/svd/vois/data/tokyo/320_Miyakejima/320_index.html Miyakejima] - Japan Meteorological Agency {{in lang|ja}}\n* {{cite web|url= http://www.data.jma.go.jp/svd/vois/data/tokyo/STOCK/souran_eng/volcanoes/062_miyakejima.pdf |title=Miyakejima: National catalogue of the active volcanoes in Japan }} - Japan Meteorological Agency\n* [https://gbank.gsj.jp/volcano/Quat_Vol/volcano_data/G07.html Miyake Jima] - Geological Survey of Japan\n* [http://volcano.si.edu/volcano.cfm?vn=284040 Miyakejima: Global Volcanism Program] - Smithsonian Institution\n\n{{Authority control}}\n\n[[Category:Izu Islands]]\n[[Category:Stratovolcanoes of Japan]]\n[[Category:Active volcanoes]]\n[[Category:Islands of Tokyo]]\n[[Category:Volcanoes of Tokyo]]\n", "name_user": "Taiga X", "label": "safe", "comment": "added photo of bus stop", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Miyake-jima"}
{"title_page": "Nova Scotia killings", "text_new": "<noinclude>{{User:RMCD bot/subject notice|1=2020 Nova Scotia attacks|2=Talk:Nova Scotia killings#Requested move 20 April 2020 }}\n</noinclude>{{pp-move-dispute|small=yes}}\n{{short description|Series of killings in Nova Scotia, Canada}}\n{{Authority control}}\n{{Current|date=April 2020}}\n{{Use mdy dates|date=April 2020}}\n{{Use Canadian English|date=April 2020}}\n{{Infobox civilian attack\n| title            = Nova Scotia killings\n{{OSM Location map\n| coord            = {{coord|45.1965|-63.3377}}\n|  zoom            = 7\n| float            = center\n| width            = 300\n| height           = 206\n| caption          =\n|   title          =\n|    minimap       = file\n|  mini-file       = Canada location map.svg\n| mini-width       = 120\n|mini-height       = 64\n|  minipog-x       = 105\n|  minipog-y       = 48\n|  scalemark       = 120 <!-- shifts the scalemark further to the left -->\n|      shape1      = image\n|       mark1      = Red pog.svg\n|      label1      = Portapique\n| mark-coord1      = {{coord|45.3972|-63.7067}}\n|  label-pos1      = bottom\n| label-size1      = 10\n|label-color1      = black\n| label-offset-x1  =\n| label-offset-y1  =\n|mark-title1       = [[Portapique, Nova Scotia]]\n|mark-image1       =\n|mark-description1 =\n\n|      label2      = Wentworth\n|       mark2      = Red pog.svg\n| mark-size2       = 8\n|  label-pos2      = left\n| label-size2      = 10\n|label-color2      = black\n| mark-coord2      = {{coord|45.6564|-63.5493}}\n|mark-title2       = [[Wentworth, Nova Scotia]]\n\n|      label3      = Shubenacadie\n|       mark3      = Red pog.svg\n| mark-size3       = 8\n|  label-pos3      = left\n| label-size3      = 10\n|label-color3      = black\n| mark-coord3      = {{coord|45.0879|-63.4019}}\n|mark-title3       = [[Shubenacadie, Nova Scotia]]\n\n|      label4      = Enfield\n|       mark4      = Red pog.svg\n| mark-size4       = 8\n|  label-pos4      = left\n| label-size4      = 10\n|label-color4      = black\n| mark-coord4      = {{coord|44.9274|-63.5366}}\n|mark-title4       = [[Enfield, Nova Scotia]]\n}}\n| partof           = \n| image            = \n| image_size       = \n| alt              = \n| caption          = \n| map              = \n| map_size         = \n| map_alt          = \n| map_caption      = Portapique in Nova Scotia\n| susperp          = \n| location         = [[Nova Scotia]], Canada\n| target           = \n| date             = {{start date|2020|4|18}}\u2013{{end date|2020|4|19}}\n| time             = \n| timezone         = [[UTC\u221203:00]]\n| coordinates      = \n| type             = [[Spree killer|Spree shooting]], [[mass shooting]],<ref name=\"Vox\" /> [[arson]]\n| weapons          = Firearm(s)\n| fatalities       = At least 19 (including the perpetrator)<ref name=\"CBC3\"/>\n| injuries         = At least 2<ref name=\"CBC3\"/>\n| victim           = \n| perp             = Gabriel Wortman\n| numparts         = \n| numpart          = \n| dfens            = \n| dfen             = \n| footage          = \n| motive           = Under investigation\n}}\n\nOn April 18 and April 19, 2020, Gabriel Wortman killed at least 18 people and set fire to at least five buildings in the [[Canadian province]] of [[Nova Scotia]] before being killed by the police following a vehicle pursuit.<ref name=\"CBC4\">{{cite news|url=https://www.cbc.ca/news/canada/nova-scotia/mass-killing-shooting-victims-remembered-1.5538032|title=Teacher, family of 3 and RCMP officer among victims of N.S. shooting rampage|publisher=CBC News|accessdate=April 20, 2020|date=April 19, 2020}}</ref>\n\nIt is the deadliest attack involving the use of firearms in Canadian history, surpassing the 1989 [[\u00c9cole Polytechnique massacre]], during which 15 people were killed.<ref name=\"AP\">{{cite news|url=https://apnews.com/7c9a33ae52420e0ddbfb5275898a7e79|title=16 killed in shooting rampage, deadliest in Canadian history|last=Gillies|first=Rob|publisher=Associated Press|accessdate=April 19, 2020|date=April 19, 2020|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200419202425/https://apnews.com/7c9a33ae52420e0ddbfb5275898a7e79|archive-date=April 19, 2020|url-status=live}}</ref> Police say the motive has not yet been established.<ref name=\"nyt-nova-scotia-shooting-gabriel-wortman\">{{Cite news|last=Diaz|first=Johnny|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2020/04/19/world/canada/nova-scotia-shooting-gabriel-wortman.html|title=Nova Scotia Shooting Kills at Least 16, Police Say|date=April 19, 2020|newspaper=[[The New York Times]]|access-date=April 19, 2020|url-status=live|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200419142013/https://www.nytimes.com/2020/04/19/world/canada/nova-scotia-shooting-gabriel-wortman.html|archive-date=April 19, 2020|last2=Bilefsky|first2=Dan}}</ref><ref name=\"Politico\">{{cite news|last=Blatchford|first=Andy|url=https://www.politico.com/news/2020/04/19/at-least-10-dead-in-canadian-shooting-rampage-195506|title=Gunman kills at least 16, including officer, in Nova Scotia|date=April 19, 2020|accessdate=April 20, 2020|publisher=Politico}}</ref>\n\n==Timeline==\nOn April 18, at around 11:00 p.m. [[Atlantic Time Zone|ADT]], [[Royal Canadian Mounted Police]] (RCMP) officers responded to multiple [[9-1-1]] calls regarding a gun-related incident in the community of [[Portapique]], {{convert|130|km|mi}} north of [[Halifax, Nova Scotia|Halifax]].<ref name=\"CBC3\">{{cite news|url=https://www.cbc.ca/news/canada/nova-scotia/mass-killings-what-we-know-what-we-don-t-1.5537918|title=Nova Scotia mass killings: What we know and what we don't know|date=April 19, 2020|accessdate=April 19, 2020|url-status=live|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200420034520/https://www.cbc.ca/news/canada/nova-scotia/mass-killings-what-we-know-what-we-don-t-1.5537918|archive-date=April 20, 2020|publisher=CBC News}}</ref><ref name=\"nyt-nova-scotia-shooting-gabriel-wortman\" /><ref name=\"CBC2\">{{cite news|url=https://www.cbc.ca/news/canada/nova-scotia/nova-scotia-timeline-active-shooter-portapique-1.5537756|title=Timeline: How an active-shooter situation unfolded in Nova Scotia|date=April 19, 2020|accessdate=April 19, 2020|url-status=live|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200420001136/https://www.cbc.ca/news/canada/nova-scotia/nova-scotia-timeline-active-shooter-portapique-1.5537756|archive-date=April 20, 2020|publisher=CBC News}}</ref><ref name=\"NBC\">{{cite news|last1=Madani|first1=Doha|url=https://www.nbcnews.com/news/world/canadian-authorities-say-mass-shooting-suspect-may-have-been-disguised-n1187381|title=16 dead, including officer, in shooting, Canadian authorities say|date=April 19, 2020|accessdate=April 19, 2020|publisher=NBC News|last2=Stelloh|first2=Tim}}</ref> Three houses on Portapique Beach Road were found on fire, and at least five victims were located; they were \"gunned down as they tried to escape the flames.\" One of the first officers to respond to the scene reported by radio that they had yet to locate an armed suspect, and that \"it's very bad what's going on down here.\"<ref name=\":2\">{{Cite news|last=Tasker|first=John Paul|url=https://www.cbc.ca/news/politics/nova-scotia-tick-tock-murder-rampage-1.5539000|title='Those scars will never heal': piecing together a gunman's murderous rampage in Nova Scotia|date=April 20, 2020|work=CBC News|access-date=April 21, 2020|url-status=live}}</ref><ref name=\"ABC\">{{cite news|last=Deliso|first=Meredith|url=https://abcnews.go.com/International/multiple-victims-canada-shooting-suspect-dressed-police-officer/story?id=70232582|title=16 dead, including police officer, in deadliest shooting in Canadian history|date=April 19, 2020|accessdate=April 19, 2020|publisher=ABC News}}</ref>\n\nAt 11:32 p.m., the RCMP sent a [[Twitter|tweet]] asking residents of the area to stay inside with their doors locked, but no message was sent through the provincial [[Emergency Alert System|emergency alert system]]. The investigation developed overnight, and by the morning of April 19, police said they were dealing with an [[active shooter]] situation.<ref name=\"CBC3\" /><ref name=\"nyt-nova-scotia-shooting-gabriel-wortman\" /><ref name=\"CBC2\" /><ref name=\"MassLive\">{{cite news|url=https://www.masslive.com/news/2020/04/nova-scotia-shooting-gabriel-wortman-kills-16-including-police-officer-in-canadas-deadliest-shooting-attack.html|title=Nova Scotia shooting: Gabriel Wortman kills 16 including police officer in Canada's deadliest shooting attack|date=April 19, 2020|accessdate=April 19, 2020|publisher=MassLive}}</ref>\n\nAt around 8:00 a.m., a 9-1-1 caller reported \"an explosion and gunfire\" at a house on Hunter Road in [[Wentworth, Nova Scotia|Wentworth]], approximately {{convert|37|km|mi}} north of Portapique. The two residents were killed, as was a neighbour who went to render assistance. Another victim was then shot and killed while walking in the community of [[Wentworth Valley]], on the road back south to Portapique.<ref name=\"CBC4\" />\n\nRCMP identified Wortman, age 51, as the suspect at 8:54 a.m., and warned that he was [[Police impersonation|dressed as an RCMP officer and operating a replica police vehicle]].<ref name=\"CBC2\" /><ref name=\"CTV\">{{cite news|last=Jerrett|first=Andrea|url=https://atlantic.ctvnews.ca/nova-scotia-shooting-suspect-shot-and-killed-by-police-1.4902687|title=At least 18 people killed in N.S. shooting; deadliest such attack in Canada: police|date=April 19, 2020|accessdate=April 19, 2020|publisher=CTV News}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|last=Shah|first=Maryam|url=https://globalnews.ca/news/6840120/nova-scotia-shooting-timeline/|title=Timeline: What we know about the Nova Scotia shooting spree|date=April 19, 2020|accessdate=April 19, 2020|publisher=Global News}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.ctvnews.ca/canada/a-timeline-of-the-deadly-shooting-incident-in-nova-scotia-1.4902954|title=A timeline of the deadly shooting incident in Nova Scotia|last1=Neustaeter|first1=Brooklyn|last2=Lopez-Martinez|first2=Melissa|date=April 19, 2020|website=CTV News|language=en|url-status=live|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200420053707/https://www.ctvnews.ca/canada/a-timeline-of-the-deadly-shooting-incident-in-nova-scotia-1.4902954|archive-date=April 20, 2020|access-date=April 19, 2020}}</ref><ref name=\"CBC\">{{cite news|url=https://www.cbc.ca/news/canada/nova-scotia/rcmp-weapon-lockdown-portapique-1.5537598|title=RCMP officer among the dead after Nova Scotia gunman's rampage|date=April 19, 2020|accessdate=April 19, 2020|url-status=live|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200419130936/https://www.cbc.ca/news/canada/nova-scotia/rcmp-weapon-lockdown-portapique-1.5537598|archive-date=April 19, 2020|publisher=CBC News}}</ref> Between 10:04 and 11:04 a.m., he was sighted in or near the communities of [[Glenholme]], [[Debert]], and [[Brookfield, Nova Scotia|Brookfield]], indicating he was travelling south along [[Nova Scotia Highway 102|Highway 102]] toward Halifax.<ref name=\":2\" /> A law enforcement source told [[CNN]] that during this time, Wortman began randomly pulling drivers over and killing them.<ref name=\"CNN\" />\n\nSometime shortly before 11:24 a.m., Wortman encountered RCMP Constable Heidi Stevenson along [[Nova Scotia Trunk 2|Highway 2]], in the community of [[Shubenacadie, Nova Scotia|Shubenacadie]]. Witnesses reported seeing Wortman run towards Stevenson and hearing an exchange of gunfire, which killed Stevenson and injured another officer.<ref name=\"CBC\" /> Two burning cars were observed at the scene, including an RCMP cruiser which may have been Wortman's replica.<ref name=\"CBC6\">{{cite news|url=https://www.cbc.ca/news/canada/nova-scotia/mass-killings-shooting-community-reaction-1.5538181|title=Death toll from Nova Scotia gunman's rampage climbs to 19|date=April 20, 2020|accessdate=April 20, 2020|publisher=CBC News}}</ref> Thereafter, he continued south in a silver [[Chevrolet Tracker (Americas)|Chevrolet Tracker]] [[Sport utility vehicle|SUV]] stolen from one of his victims, and he was next seen in [[Milford (Halifax), Nova Scotia|Milford]].<ref name=\"CBC2\" /><ref name=\"BBC\">{{cite news|url=https://www.bbc.com/news/world-us-canada-52346447|title=Canada shooting: Gunman kills at least 18 in Nova Scotia|date=April 19, 2020|accessdate=April 19, 2020|url-status=live|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200419211041/https://www.bbc.com/news/world-us-canada-52346447|archive-date=April 19, 2020|publisher=BBC News}}</ref>\n\nFinally, at 11:40 a.m., over 12 hours after police responded to the first firearms complaint, Wortman was shot and killed by police at the [[Irving Oil|Irving]] Big Stop gas station in [[Enfield, Nova Scotia|Enfield]], about {{convert|92|km|mi}} south of Portapique and about {{convert|40|km|mi}} north of Halifax.<ref name=\"Vox\">{{cite news|last=Collins|first=Sean|url=https://www.vox.com/world/2020/4/19/21227349/mass-shooting-nova-scotia-canada-enfield-portapique|title=What we know about a mass shooting in Nova Scotia, Canada|date=April 19, 2020|accessdate=April 19, 2020|publisher=Vox}}</ref><ref name=\"CBC2\" /><ref name=\"CTV\" />\n\n==Investigation==\nNo motive has been established for the killings, although they are not considered by police to be an act of [[terrorism in Canada|terrorism]].<ref name=\"nyt-nova-scotia-shooting-gabriel-wortman\" />\n\nOn the afternoon of April 20, RCMP Chief Superintendent Chris Leather said there were 16 crime scenes in total, including five structure fires, which were scattered over a distance of at least {{convert|50|km|mi}}. He said he expected the death toll to rise as these crime scenes are investigated further.<ref name=\"CBC6\" />\n\nCiting an unnamed law enforcement source, CNN reported that the incident may have begun as a case of domestic violence at one of the homes in Portapique, where Wortman was allegedly trying to find a former partner.<ref name=\"CNN\" />\n\n[[Nova Scotia]]'s [[Serious Incident Response Team]] (SIRT) announced it would conduct an investigation into the officer-involved shooting, as well as a second police use-of-force incident.<ref name=\"CBC\" /><ref name=\"CBC6\" /><ref>{{cite web|url=https://sirt.novascotia.ca/investigation-begins-enfield-death|title=INVESTIGATION BEGINS INTO ENFIELD DEATH|publisher=Serious Incident Response Team|date=April 19, 2020|accessdate=April 20, 2020}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://sirt.novascotia.ca/sirt-investigate-discharge-firearm-rcmp-officers|title=SIRT TO INVESTIGATE DISCHARGE OF FIREARM BY RCMP OFFICERS|publisher=Serious Incident Response Team|date=April 20, 2020|accessdate=April 20, 2020}}</ref>\n\nQuestions were raised about why Nova Scotia did not use its [[emergency alert system]] to warn the public about the killings. The RCMP used Twitter to provide updates, but the areas affected had poor Internet service and were mostly populated by seniors who might not use social media. Usage of Nova Scotia's emergency alert system would have sent text messages advising residents of what was happening and to stay indoors. Superintendent Leather said an investigation would be conducted into the decision-making process to alert the public.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.cbc.ca/news/canada/nova-scotia/ns-public-alert-1.5538286|title=N.S. premier not ready to question if a public alert should have been issued about gunman|publisher=CBC News|last=Gorman|first=Michael|date=April 20, 2020|accessdate=April 20, 2020}}</ref>\n\n==Victims==\nWortman killed at least 18 people, one of them RCMP Constable Heidi Stevenson, a 23-year veteran. He shot and wounded a second RCMP officer, who is in stable condition.<ref name=\"CBC3\"/><ref name=\"CBC\" /><ref name=\"global-news-rcmp-active-shooter-portapique-n-s\">{{Cite news|last=Quon|first=Alexander|url=https://globalnews.ca/news/6838880/rcmp-active-shooter-portapique-n-s/|title=17 dead, including one RCMP officer, after shooting spree in Portapique, N.S.|date=April 19, 2020|access-date=April 19, 2020|url-status=live|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200419202613/https://globalnews.ca/news/6838880/rcmp-active-shooter-portapique-n-s/|archive-date=April 19, 2020|publisher=[[Global News]]|last2=Stephenson|first2=Mercedes}}</ref> At least one other person was injured.<ref name=\"CBC3\" /> According to Commissioner [[Brenda Lucki]], some of his first victims were closely connected to him, but as he continued, his targets became more random.<ref name=\"nyt-nova-scotia-shooting-gabriel-wortman\" /> The dead are believed to have died from gunshot wounds, but other causes are also being investigated.<ref name=\"CBC3\" /><ref name=\"BBC\" /> The RCMP expects to find more bodies within the remnants of five structure fires.<ref name=\"CTV4\">{{cite web|url=https://www.ctvnews.ca/canada/nova-scotia-rampage-results-in-18-victims-16-crime-scenes-1.4903398|title=Nova Scotia rampage results in 18 victims, 16 crime scenes|date=April 20, 2020|work=[[CTV News]]|first=Meredith|last=MacLeod|accessdate=April 20, 2020}}</ref>\n\n==Perpetrator==\nThe RCMP identified the perpetrator as Gabriel Wortman, a [[denturist]] working in the Halifax area. He owned real estate in Portapique and [[Dartmouth, Nova Scotia|Dartmouth]].<ref name=\"CBC\"/><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.theguardian.com/world/2020/apr/20/nova-scotia-shooting-gunman-profile-quiet-gentle-denturist|title=Nova Scotia shooting: shock and surprise at killings by denturist|first=Leyland|last=Cecco|date=April 19, 2020|accessdate=April 19, 2020|website=The Guardian}}</ref> He attended [[Riverview High School (New Brunswick)|Riverview High School]] in New Brunswick and aspired to be a police officer.<ref name=\":1\">{{Cite web|url=https://atlantic.ctvnews.ca/just-unbelievable-neighbours-of-nova-scotia-shooting-suspect-shocked-by-news-1.4903021|title='Just unbelievable': Neighbours of Nova Scotia shooting suspect shocked by news|date=April 19, 2020|website=CTV News|language=en|access-date=April 20, 2020}}</ref> Acquaintances described him as a house-proud and polite man who often spent time at a seasonal home near [[Cobequid Bay]].<ref name=\"CTV5\">{{cite news|url=https://www.ctvnews.ca/canada/what-we-know-about-the-nova-scotia-rampage-suspect-1.4903920|title=What we know about the Nova Scotia rampage suspect|publisher=CTV News|last=Bogart|first=Nicole|date=April 20, 2020|accessdate=April 20, 2020}}</ref>\n\nWortman had a hobby of buying law enforcement memorabilia and refurbishing old police cruisers. One person called his home a \"shrine\" for the RCMP.<ref name=\":0\">{{cite news|url=https://www.theglobeandmail.com/canada/article-nova-scotia-mass-shooter-was-a-denturist-with-an-obsession-for/|title=Nova Scotia mass shooter was a denturist with an obsession for policing|publisher=The Globe and Mail|last1=Woo|first1=Andrew|last2=Mercer|first2=Greg|date=April 19, 2020|accessdate=April 20, 2020|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200420055810/https://www.theglobeandmail.com/canada/article-nova-scotia-mass-shooter-was-a-denturist-with-an-obsession-for/|archive-date=April 20, 2020|url-status=live}}</ref> He stored the two old police cruisers that he bought behind his dental clinic.<ref name=\":1\" /><ref name=\"CTV5\" />\n\nNeighbours said Wortman struggled with [[alcohol use]] and his profitable business was impacted by the [[2020 coronavirus pandemic in Nova Scotia|coronavirus pandemic]], which forced all non-essential dental services to cease.<ref name=\":0\" />\n\n==Reactions==\n[[Nova Scotia Premier]] [[Stephen McNeil]] told reporters, \"This is one of the most senseless acts of violence in our province's history.\" He expressed his condolences to the residents affected and the families of the victims.<ref name=\"CTV2\">{{cite news|url=https://atlantic.ctvnews.ca/shooting-one-of-the-most-senseless-acts-of-violence-in-nova-scotia-s-history-premier-1.4902917|title=Shooting 'one of the most senseless acts of violence' in Nova Scotia's history: premier|last=Jerrett|first=Andrea|publisher=CTV News|accessdate=April 19, 2020|date=April 19, 2020}}</ref> Prime Minister [[Justin Trudeau]] also expressed his condolences.<ref name=\"CBC\" /> During his morning address from [[Rideau Cottage]] on April 20, he reaffirmed his commitment to strengthening gun control.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.ctvnews.ca/politics/trudeau-reiterates-gun-control-commitment-in-wake-of-mass-shooting-1.4903966|title=Trudeau reiterates gun control commitment in wake of mass shooting|publisher=CTV News|last=Gilmore|first=Rachel|date=April 20, 2020|accessdate=April 20, 2020}}</ref> Flags across Canada were lowered to [[half-mast]],<ref name=\"Guardian2\">{{cite news|url=https://www.theguardian.com/world/2020/apr/20/nova-scotia-shooting-friends-family-pay-tribute-victims|title=Nova Scotia shooting: friends and family pay tribute to 'beautiful souls' lost in rampage|publisher=The Guardian|last=Cecco|first=Leyland|date=April 20, 2020|accessdate=April 20, 2020}}</ref> and the [[House of Commons of Canada|House of Commons]] observed a moment of silence for the victims.<ref>{{cite web| url=https://www.cbc.ca/news/politics/trudeau-nova-scotia-shooting-1.5538301| title='We're going to get through this together': Trudeau calls for unity after mass killing| website=CBC News| date=April 20, 2020| accessdate=April 20, 2020| url-status=live| archive-url=http://archive.is/7qFSQ| archive-date=April 20, 2020}}</ref>\n\nThe [[White House]] released a statement that condemned the killings and expressed US President [[Donald Trump]] and US First Lady [[Melania Trump]]'s condolences.<ref name=\"CNN\">{{cite news|url=https://www.cnn.com/2020/04/20/americas/nova-scotia-shooting-monday/index.html|title=Gunman evaded police for nearly 12 hours and killed at least 18 in one of Canada's deadliest mass shootings|publisher=CNN|last1=McLaughlin|first1=Eliott C.|last2=Newton|first2=Paula|date=April 20, 2020|accessdate=April 20, 2020}}</ref>\n\n==See also==\n* [[Moncton shooting]]\n* [[List of massacres in Canada]]\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n[[Category:2020 crimes in Canada]]\n[[Category:2020 in Nova Scotia]]\n[[Category:2020 mass shootings]]\n[[Category:2020 mass shootings in North America]]\n[[Category:2020 murders in North America]]\n[[Category:2020s mass shootings in North America]]\n[[Category:21st-century mass murder in North America]]\n[[Category:April 2020 crimes]]\n[[Category:April 2020 events in Canada]]\n[[Category:Arson in Canada]]\n[[Category:Arson in the 2020s]]\n[[Category:Attacks in 2020]]\n[[Category:Crime in Nova Scotia]]\n[[Category:Death in Nova Scotia]]\n[[Category:Deaths by firearm in Canada]]\n[[Category:Mass shootings in Canada]]\n[[Category:Mass murder in Canada]]\n[[Category:Royal Canadian Mounted Police]]\n[[Category:Spree shootings in Canada]]\n", "text_old": "<noinclude>{{User:RMCD bot/subject notice|1=2020 Nova Scotia attacks|2=Talk:Nova Scotia killings#Requested move 20 April 2020 }}\n</noinclude>{{pp-move-dispute|small=yes}}\n{{short description|Series of killings in Nova Scotia, Canada}}\n{{Authority control}}\n{{Current|date=April 2020}}\n{{Use mdy dates|date=April 2020}}\n{{Use Canadian English|date=April 2020}}\n{{Infobox civilian attack\n| title            = Nova Scotia killings\n{{OSM Location map\n| coord            = {{coord|45.1965|-63.3377}}\n|  zoom            = 7\n| float            = center\n| width            = 300\n| height           = 206\n| caption          =\n|   title          =\n|    minimap       = file\n|  mini-file       = Canada location map.svg\n| mini-width       = 120\n|mini-height       = 64\n|  minipog-x       = 105\n|  minipog-y       = 48\n|  scalemark       = 120 <!-- shifts the scalemark further to the left -->\n|      shape1      = image\n|       mark1      = Red pog.svg\n|      label1      = Portapique\n| mark-coord1      = {{coord|45.3972|-63.7067}}\n|  label-pos1      = bottom\n| label-size1      = 10\n|label-color1      = black\n| label-offset-x1  =\n| label-offset-y1  =\n|mark-title1       = [[Portapique, Nova Scotia]]\n|mark-image1       =\n|mark-description1 =\n\n|      label2      = Wentworth\n|       mark2      = Red pog.svg\n| mark-size2       = 8\n|  label-pos2      = left\n| label-size2      = 10\n|label-color2      = black\n| mark-coord2      = {{coord|45.6564|-63.5493}}\n|mark-title2       = [[Wentworth, Nova Scotia]]\n\n|      label3      = Shubenacadie\n|       mark3      = Red pog.svg\n| mark-size3       = 8\n|  label-pos3      = left\n| label-size3      = 10\n|label-color3      = black\n| mark-coord3      = {{coord|45.0879|-63.4019}}\n|mark-title3       = [[Shubenacadie, Nova Scotia]]\n\n|      label4      = Enfield\n|       mark4      = Red pog.svg\n| mark-size4       = 8\n|  label-pos4      = left\n| label-size4      = 10\n|label-color4      = black\n| mark-coord4      = {{coord|44.9274|-63.5366}}\n|mark-title4       = [[Enfield, Nova Scotia]]\n}}\n| partof           = \n| image            = \n| image_size       = \n| alt              = \n| caption          = \n| map              = \n| map_size         = \n| map_alt          = \n| map_caption      = Portapique in Nova Scotia\n| susperp          = \n| location         = [[Nova Scotia]], Canada\n| target           = \n| date             = {{start date|2020|4|18}}\u2013{{end date|2020|4|19}}\n| time             = \n| timezone         = [[UTC\u221203:00]]\n| coordinates      = \n| type             = [[Spree killer|Spree shooting]], [[mass shooting]],<ref name=\"Vox\" /> [[arson]]\n| weapons          = Firearm(s)\n| fatalities       = At least 19 (including the perpetrator)<ref name=\"CBC3\"/>\n| injuries         = At least 2<ref name=\"CBC3\"/>\n| victim           = \n| perp             = Gabriel Wortman\n| numparts         = \n| numpart          = \n| dfens            = \n| dfen             = \n| footage          = \n| motive           = Under investigation\n}}\n\nOn April 18 and April 19, 2020, Gabriel Wortman killed at least 18 people and set fire to at least five buildings in the [[Canadian province]] of [[Nova Scotia]] before being killed by the police following a vehicle pursuit.<ref name=\"CBC4\">{{cite news|url=https://www.cbc.ca/news/canada/nova-scotia/mass-killing-shooting-victims-remembered-1.5538032|title=Teacher, family of 3 and RCMP officer among victims of N.S. shooting rampage|publisher=CBC News|accessdate=April 20, 2020|date=April 19, 2020}}</ref>\n\nIt is the deadliest attack involving the use of firearms in Canadian history, surpassing the 1989 [[\u00c9cole Polytechnique massacre]], during which 15 people were killed.<ref name=\"AP\">{{cite news|url=https://apnews.com/7c9a33ae52420e0ddbfb5275898a7e79|title=16 killed in shooting rampage, deadliest in Canadian history|last=Gillies|first=Rob|publisher=Associated Press|accessdate=April 19, 2020|date=April 19, 2020|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200419202425/https://apnews.com/7c9a33ae52420e0ddbfb5275898a7e79|archive-date=April 19, 2020|url-status=live}}</ref> Police say the motive has not yet been established.<ref name=\"nyt-nova-scotia-shooting-gabriel-wortman\">{{Cite news|last=Diaz|first=Johnny|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2020/04/19/world/canada/nova-scotia-shooting-gabriel-wortman.html|title=Nova Scotia Shooting Kills at Least 16, Police Say|date=April 19, 2020|newspaper=[[The New York Times]]|access-date=April 19, 2020|url-status=live|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200419142013/https://www.nytimes.com/2020/04/19/world/canada/nova-scotia-shooting-gabriel-wortman.html|archive-date=April 19, 2020|last2=Bilefsky|first2=Dan}}</ref><ref name=\"Politico\">{{cite news|last=Blatchford|first=Andy|url=https://www.politico.com/news/2020/04/19/at-least-10-dead-in-canadian-shooting-rampage-195506|title=Gunman kills at least 16, including officer, in Nova Scotia|date=April 19, 2020|accessdate=April 20, 2020|publisher=Politico}}</ref>\n\n==Timeline==\nOn April 18, at around 11:00 p.m. [[Atlantic Time Zone|ADT]], [[Royal Canadian Mounted Police]] (RCMP) officers responded to multiple [[9-1-1]] calls regarding a gun-related incident in the community of [[Portapique]], {{convert|130|km|mi}} north of [[Halifax, Nova Scotia|Halifax]].<ref name=\"CBC3\">{{cite news|url=https://www.cbc.ca/news/canada/nova-scotia/mass-killings-what-we-know-what-we-don-t-1.5537918|title=Nova Scotia mass killings: What we know and what we don't know|date=April 19, 2020|accessdate=April 19, 2020|url-status=live|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200420034520/https://www.cbc.ca/news/canada/nova-scotia/mass-killings-what-we-know-what-we-don-t-1.5537918|archive-date=April 20, 2020|publisher=CBC News}}</ref><ref name=\"nyt-nova-scotia-shooting-gabriel-wortman\" /><ref name=\"CBC2\">{{cite news|url=https://www.cbc.ca/news/canada/nova-scotia/nova-scotia-timeline-active-shooter-portapique-1.5537756|title=Timeline: How an active-shooter situation unfolded in Nova Scotia|date=April 19, 2020|accessdate=April 19, 2020|url-status=live|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200420001136/https://www.cbc.ca/news/canada/nova-scotia/nova-scotia-timeline-active-shooter-portapique-1.5537756|archive-date=April 20, 2020|publisher=CBC News}}</ref><ref name=\"NBC\">{{cite news|last1=Madani|first1=Doha|url=https://www.nbcnews.com/news/world/canadian-authorities-say-mass-shooting-suspect-may-have-been-disguised-n1187381|title=16 dead, including officer, in shooting, Canadian authorities say|date=April 19, 2020|accessdate=April 19, 2020|publisher=NBC News|last2=Stelloh|first2=Tim}}</ref> Three houses on Portapique Beach Road were found on fire, and at least five victims were located; they were \"gunned down as they tried to escape the flames.\" One of the first officers to respond to the scene reported by radio that they had yet to locate an armed suspect, and that \"it's very bad what's going on down here.\"<ref name=\":2\">{{Cite news|last=Tasker|first=John Paul|url=https://www.cbc.ca/news/politics/nova-scotia-tick-tock-murder-rampage-1.5539000|title='Those scars will never heal': piecing together a gunman's murderous rampage in Nova Scotia|date=April 20, 2020|work=CBC News|access-date=April 21, 2020|url-status=live}}</ref><ref name=\"ABC\">{{cite news|last=Deliso|first=Meredith|url=https://abcnews.go.com/International/multiple-victims-canada-shooting-suspect-dressed-police-officer/story?id=70232582|title=16 dead, including police officer, in deadliest shooting in Canadian history|date=April 19, 2020|accessdate=April 19, 2020|publisher=ABC News}}</ref>\n\nAt 11:32 p.m., the RCMP sent a [[Twitter|tweet]] asking residents of the area to stay inside with their doors locked, but no message was sent through the provincial [[Emergency Alert System|emergency alert system]]. The investigation developed overnight, and by the morning of April 19, police said they were dealing with an [[active shooter]] situation.<ref name=\"CBC3\" /><ref name=\"nyt-nova-scotia-shooting-gabriel-wortman\" /><ref name=\"CBC2\" /><ref name=\"MassLive\">{{cite news|url=https://www.masslive.com/news/2020/04/nova-scotia-shooting-gabriel-wortman-kills-16-including-police-officer-in-canadas-deadliest-shooting-attack.html|title=Nova Scotia shooting: Gabriel Wortman kills 16 including police officer in Canada's deadliest shooting attack|date=April 19, 2020|accessdate=April 19, 2020|publisher=MassLive}}</ref>\n\nAt around 8:00 a.m., a 9-1-1 caller reported \"an explosion and gunfire\" at a house on Hunter Road in [[Wentworth, Nova Scotia|Wentworth]], approximately {{convert|37|km|mi}} north of Portapique. The two residents were killed, as was a neighbour who went to render assistance. Another victim was then allegedly shot and killed while walking in the community of [[Wentworth Valley]], on the road back south to Portapique.<ref name=\"CBC4\" />\n\nRCMP identified Wortman, age 51, as the suspect at 8:54 a.m., and warned that he was [[Police impersonation|dressed as an RCMP officer and operating a replica police vehicle]].<ref name=\"CBC2\" /><ref name=\"CTV\">{{cite news|last=Jerrett|first=Andrea|url=https://atlantic.ctvnews.ca/nova-scotia-shooting-suspect-shot-and-killed-by-police-1.4902687|title=At least 18 people killed in N.S. shooting; deadliest such attack in Canada: police|date=April 19, 2020|accessdate=April 19, 2020|publisher=CTV News}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|last=Shah|first=Maryam|url=https://globalnews.ca/news/6840120/nova-scotia-shooting-timeline/|title=Timeline: What we know about the Nova Scotia shooting spree|date=April 19, 2020|accessdate=April 19, 2020|publisher=Global News}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.ctvnews.ca/canada/a-timeline-of-the-deadly-shooting-incident-in-nova-scotia-1.4902954|title=A timeline of the deadly shooting incident in Nova Scotia|last1=Neustaeter|first1=Brooklyn|last2=Lopez-Martinez|first2=Melissa|date=April 19, 2020|website=CTV News|language=en|url-status=live|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200420053707/https://www.ctvnews.ca/canada/a-timeline-of-the-deadly-shooting-incident-in-nova-scotia-1.4902954|archive-date=April 20, 2020|access-date=April 19, 2020}}</ref><ref name=\"CBC\">{{cite news|url=https://www.cbc.ca/news/canada/nova-scotia/rcmp-weapon-lockdown-portapique-1.5537598|title=RCMP officer among the dead after Nova Scotia gunman's rampage|date=April 19, 2020|accessdate=April 19, 2020|url-status=live|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200419130936/https://www.cbc.ca/news/canada/nova-scotia/rcmp-weapon-lockdown-portapique-1.5537598|archive-date=April 19, 2020|publisher=CBC News}}</ref> Between 10:04 and 11:04 a.m., he was sighted in or near the communities of [[Glenholme]], [[Debert]], and [[Brookfield, Nova Scotia|Brookfield]], indicating he was travelling south along [[Nova Scotia Highway 102|Highway 102]] toward Halifax.<ref name=\":2\" /> A law enforcement source told [[CNN]] that during this time, Wortman began randomly pulling drivers over and killing them.<ref name=\"CNN\" />\n\nSometime shortly before 11:24 a.m., Wortman encountered RCMP Constable Heidi Stevenson along [[Nova Scotia Trunk 2|Highway 2]], in the community of [[Shubenacadie, Nova Scotia|Shubenacadie]]. Witnesses reported seeing Wortman run towards Stevenson and hearing an exchange of gunfire, which killed Stevenson and injured another officer.<ref name=\"CBC\" /> Two burning cars were observed at the scene, including an RCMP cruiser which may have been Wortman's replica.<ref name=\"CBC6\">{{cite news|url=https://www.cbc.ca/news/canada/nova-scotia/mass-killings-shooting-community-reaction-1.5538181|title=Death toll from Nova Scotia gunman's rampage climbs to 19|date=April 20, 2020|accessdate=April 20, 2020|publisher=CBC News}}</ref> Thereafter, he continued south in a silver [[Chevrolet Tracker (Americas)|Chevrolet Tracker]] [[Sport utility vehicle|SUV]] stolen from one of his victims, and he was next seen in [[Milford (Halifax), Nova Scotia|Milford]].<ref name=\"CBC2\" /><ref name=\"BBC\">{{cite news|url=https://www.bbc.com/news/world-us-canada-52346447|title=Canada shooting: Gunman kills at least 18 in Nova Scotia|date=April 19, 2020|accessdate=April 19, 2020|url-status=live|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200419211041/https://www.bbc.com/news/world-us-canada-52346447|archive-date=April 19, 2020|publisher=BBC News}}</ref>\n\nFinally, at 11:40 a.m., over 12 hours after police responded to the first firearms complaint, Wortman was shot and killed by police at the [[Irving Oil|Irving]] Big Stop gas station in [[Enfield, Nova Scotia|Enfield]], about {{convert|92|km|mi}} south of Portapique and about {{convert|40|km|mi}} north of Halifax.<ref name=\"Vox\">{{cite news|last=Collins|first=Sean|url=https://www.vox.com/world/2020/4/19/21227349/mass-shooting-nova-scotia-canada-enfield-portapique|title=What we know about a mass shooting in Nova Scotia, Canada|date=April 19, 2020|accessdate=April 19, 2020|publisher=Vox}}</ref><ref name=\"CBC2\" /><ref name=\"CTV\" />\n\n==Investigation==\nNo motive has been established for the killings, although they are not considered by police to be an act of [[terrorism in Canada|terrorism]].<ref name=\"nyt-nova-scotia-shooting-gabriel-wortman\" />\n\nOn the afternoon of April 20, RCMP Chief Superintendent Chris Leather said there were 16 crime scenes in total, including five structure fires, which were scattered over a distance of at least {{convert|50|km|mi}}. He said he expected the death toll to rise as these crime scenes are investigated further.<ref name=\"CBC6\" />\n\nCiting an unnamed law enforcement source, CNN reported that the incident may have begun as a case of domestic violence at one of the homes in Portapique, where Wortman was allegedly trying to find a former partner.<ref name=\"CNN\" />\n\n[[Nova Scotia]]'s [[Serious Incident Response Team]] (SIRT) announced it would conduct an investigation into the officer-involved shooting, as well as a second police use-of-force incident.<ref name=\"CBC\" /><ref name=\"CBC6\" /><ref>{{cite web|url=https://sirt.novascotia.ca/investigation-begins-enfield-death|title=INVESTIGATION BEGINS INTO ENFIELD DEATH|publisher=Serious Incident Response Team|date=April 19, 2020|accessdate=April 20, 2020}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://sirt.novascotia.ca/sirt-investigate-discharge-firearm-rcmp-officers|title=SIRT TO INVESTIGATE DISCHARGE OF FIREARM BY RCMP OFFICERS|publisher=Serious Incident Response Team|date=April 20, 2020|accessdate=April 20, 2020}}</ref>\n\nQuestions were raised about why Nova Scotia did not use its [[emergency alert system]] to warn the public about the killings. The RCMP used Twitter to provide updates, but the areas affected had poor Internet service and were mostly populated by seniors who might not use social media. Usage of Nova Scotia's emergency alert system would have sent text messages advising residents of what was happening and to stay indoors. Superintendent Leather said an investigation would be conducted into the decision-making process to alert the public.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.cbc.ca/news/canada/nova-scotia/ns-public-alert-1.5538286|title=N.S. premier not ready to question if a public alert should have been issued about gunman|publisher=CBC News|last=Gorman|first=Michael|date=April 20, 2020|accessdate=April 20, 2020}}</ref>\n\n==Victims==\nWortman killed at least 18 people, one of them RCMP Constable Heidi Stevenson, a 23-year veteran. He shot and wounded a second RCMP officer, who is in stable condition.<ref name=\"CBC3\"/><ref name=\"CBC\" /><ref name=\"global-news-rcmp-active-shooter-portapique-n-s\">{{Cite news|last=Quon|first=Alexander|url=https://globalnews.ca/news/6838880/rcmp-active-shooter-portapique-n-s/|title=17 dead, including one RCMP officer, after shooting spree in Portapique, N.S.|date=April 19, 2020|access-date=April 19, 2020|url-status=live|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200419202613/https://globalnews.ca/news/6838880/rcmp-active-shooter-portapique-n-s/|archive-date=April 19, 2020|publisher=[[Global News]]|last2=Stephenson|first2=Mercedes}}</ref> At least one other person was injured.<ref name=\"CBC3\" /> According to Commissioner [[Brenda Lucki]], some of his first victims were closely connected to him, but as he continued, his targets became more random.<ref name=\"nyt-nova-scotia-shooting-gabriel-wortman\" /> The dead are believed to have died from gunshot wounds, but other causes are also being investigated.<ref name=\"CBC3\" /><ref name=\"BBC\" /> The RCMP expects to find more bodies within the remnants of five structure fires.<ref name=\"CTV4\">{{cite web|url=https://www.ctvnews.ca/canada/nova-scotia-rampage-results-in-18-victims-16-crime-scenes-1.4903398|title=Nova Scotia rampage results in 18 victims, 16 crime scenes|date=April 20, 2020|work=[[CTV News]]|first=Meredith|last=MacLeod|accessdate=April 20, 2020}}</ref>\n\n==Perpetrator==\nThe RCMP identified the perpetrator as Gabriel Wortman, a [[denturist]] working in the Halifax area. He owned real estate in Portapique and [[Dartmouth, Nova Scotia|Dartmouth]].<ref name=\"CBC\"/><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.theguardian.com/world/2020/apr/20/nova-scotia-shooting-gunman-profile-quiet-gentle-denturist|title=Nova Scotia shooting: shock and surprise at killings by denturist|first=Leyland|last=Cecco|date=April 19, 2020|accessdate=April 19, 2020|website=The Guardian}}</ref> He attended [[Riverview High School (New Brunswick)|Riverview High School]] in New Brunswick and aspired to be a police officer.<ref name=\":1\">{{Cite web|url=https://atlantic.ctvnews.ca/just-unbelievable-neighbours-of-nova-scotia-shooting-suspect-shocked-by-news-1.4903021|title='Just unbelievable': Neighbours of Nova Scotia shooting suspect shocked by news|date=April 19, 2020|website=CTV News|language=en|access-date=April 20, 2020}}</ref> Acquaintances described him as a house-proud and polite man who often spent time at a seasonal home near [[Cobequid Bay]].<ref name=\"CTV5\">{{cite news|url=https://www.ctvnews.ca/canada/what-we-know-about-the-nova-scotia-rampage-suspect-1.4903920|title=What we know about the Nova Scotia rampage suspect|publisher=CTV News|last=Bogart|first=Nicole|date=April 20, 2020|accessdate=April 20, 2020}}</ref>\n\nWortman had a hobby of buying law enforcement memorabilia and refurbishing old police cruisers. One person called his home a \"shrine\" for the RCMP.<ref name=\":0\">{{cite news|url=https://www.theglobeandmail.com/canada/article-nova-scotia-mass-shooter-was-a-denturist-with-an-obsession-for/|title=Nova Scotia mass shooter was a denturist with an obsession for policing|publisher=The Globe and Mail|last1=Woo|first1=Andrew|last2=Mercer|first2=Greg|date=April 19, 2020|accessdate=April 20, 2020|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200420055810/https://www.theglobeandmail.com/canada/article-nova-scotia-mass-shooter-was-a-denturist-with-an-obsession-for/|archive-date=April 20, 2020|url-status=live}}</ref> He stored the two old police cruisers that he bought behind his dental clinic.<ref name=\":1\" /><ref name=\"CTV5\" />\n\nNeighbours said Wortman struggled with [[alcohol use]] and his profitable business was impacted by the [[2020 coronavirus pandemic in Nova Scotia|coronavirus pandemic]], which forced all non-essential dental services to cease.<ref name=\":0\" />\n\n==Reactions==\n[[Nova Scotia Premier]] [[Stephen McNeil]] told reporters, \"This is one of the most senseless acts of violence in our province's history.\" He expressed his condolences to the residents affected and the families of the victims.<ref name=\"CTV2\">{{cite news|url=https://atlantic.ctvnews.ca/shooting-one-of-the-most-senseless-acts-of-violence-in-nova-scotia-s-history-premier-1.4902917|title=Shooting 'one of the most senseless acts of violence' in Nova Scotia's history: premier|last=Jerrett|first=Andrea|publisher=CTV News|accessdate=April 19, 2020|date=April 19, 2020}}</ref> Prime Minister [[Justin Trudeau]] also expressed his condolences.<ref name=\"CBC\" /> During his morning address from [[Rideau Cottage]] on April 20, he reaffirmed his commitment to strengthening gun control.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.ctvnews.ca/politics/trudeau-reiterates-gun-control-commitment-in-wake-of-mass-shooting-1.4903966|title=Trudeau reiterates gun control commitment in wake of mass shooting|publisher=CTV News|last=Gilmore|first=Rachel|date=April 20, 2020|accessdate=April 20, 2020}}</ref> Flags across Canada were lowered to [[half-mast]],<ref name=\"Guardian2\">{{cite news|url=https://www.theguardian.com/world/2020/apr/20/nova-scotia-shooting-friends-family-pay-tribute-victims|title=Nova Scotia shooting: friends and family pay tribute to 'beautiful souls' lost in rampage|publisher=The Guardian|last=Cecco|first=Leyland|date=April 20, 2020|accessdate=April 20, 2020}}</ref> and the [[House of Commons of Canada|House of Commons]] observed a moment of silence for the victims.<ref>{{cite web| url=https://www.cbc.ca/news/politics/trudeau-nova-scotia-shooting-1.5538301| title='We're going to get through this together': Trudeau calls for unity after mass killing| website=CBC News| date=April 20, 2020| accessdate=April 20, 2020| url-status=live| archive-url=http://archive.is/7qFSQ| archive-date=April 20, 2020}}</ref>\n\nThe [[White House]] released a statement that condemned the killings and expressed US President [[Donald Trump]] and US First Lady [[Melania Trump]]'s condolences.<ref name=\"CNN\">{{cite news|url=https://www.cnn.com/2020/04/20/americas/nova-scotia-shooting-monday/index.html|title=Gunman evaded police for nearly 12 hours and killed at least 18 in one of Canada's deadliest mass shootings|publisher=CNN|last1=McLaughlin|first1=Eliott C.|last2=Newton|first2=Paula|date=April 20, 2020|accessdate=April 20, 2020}}</ref>\n\n==See also==\n* [[Moncton shooting]]\n* [[List of massacres in Canada]]\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n[[Category:2020 crimes in Canada]]\n[[Category:2020 in Nova Scotia]]\n[[Category:2020 mass shootings]]\n[[Category:2020 mass shootings in North America]]\n[[Category:2020 murders in North America]]\n[[Category:2020s mass shootings in North America]]\n[[Category:21st-century mass murder in North America]]\n[[Category:April 2020 crimes]]\n[[Category:April 2020 events in Canada]]\n[[Category:Arson in Canada]]\n[[Category:Arson in the 2020s]]\n[[Category:Attacks in 2020]]\n[[Category:Crime in Nova Scotia]]\n[[Category:Death in Nova Scotia]]\n[[Category:Deaths by firearm in Canada]]\n[[Category:Mass shootings in Canada]]\n[[Category:Mass murder in Canada]]\n[[Category:Royal Canadian Mounted Police]]\n[[Category:Spree shootings in Canada]]\n", "name_user": "InedibleHulk", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200eTimeline:Not needed when the scumbags are dead.", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Nova_Scotia_killings"}
{"title_page": "Marquez, Texas", "text_new": "{{Infobox settlement\n|official_name            = Marquez, Texas\n|settlement_type          = [[City]]\n|nickname                 = The wolf den\n|motto                    =\n\n<!-- Images -->\n|image_skyline            = Post Office, Marquez, TX IMG_4441.JPG\n|imagesize                = 200px\n|image_caption            = Marquez Post Office\n|image_flag               = \n|image_seal               =\n\n<!-- Maps -->\n|image_map                = TXMap-doton-Marquez.PNG\n|mapsize                  = 250px\n|map_caption              = Location of Marquez, Texas\n|image_map1               = Leon County Marquez.svg\n|mapsize1                 = 250px\n|map_caption1             =\n\n<!-- Location -->\n|subdivision_type         = [[List of sovereign states|Country]]\n|subdivision_name         = United States\n|subdivision_type1        = [[U.S. state|State]]\n|subdivision_name1        = [[Texas]]\n|subdivision_type2        = [[List of counties in Texas|County]]\n|subdivision_name2        = [[Leon County, Texas|Leon]]\n\n<!-- Government -->\n|government_footnotes     = \n|government_type          = \n|leader_title             = \n|leader_name              = \n|leader_title1            = \n|leader_name1             = \n|established_title        = \n|established_date         =\n\n<!-- Area -->\n|unit_pref  =  Imperial\n|area_footnotes           = \n|area_magnitude           = \n|area_total_km2           = 3.1\n|area_land_km2            = 3.1\n|area_water_km2           = 0.0\n|area_total_sq_mi         = 1.2\n|area_land_sq_mi          = 1.2\n|area_water_sq_mi         = 0.0\n\n<!-- Population -->\n|population_as_of         = [[United States Census, 2000|2000]]\n|population_footnotes     = \n|population_total         = 383\n|population_density_km2   = 70.8\n|population_density_sq_mi = 183.3\n\n<!-- General information -->\n|timezone                 = [[North American Central Time Zone|Central (CST)]]\n|utc_offset               = -6\n|timezone_DST             = CDT\n|utc_offset_DST           = -5\n|elevation_footnotes      = \n|elevation_m              = 124\n|elevation_ft             = 407\n|coordinates              = {{coord|31|14|24|N|96|15|19|W|region:US-TX|display=inline,title}}\n|postal_code_type         = [[ZIP code]]\n|postal_code              = 77865\n|area_code                = [[Area code 903|903]]\n|blank_name               = [[Federal Information Processing Standard|FIPS code]]\n|blank_info               = 48-46752<ref name=\"GR2\">{{cite web|url=https://www.census.gov|publisher=[[United States Census Bureau]]|accessdate=2008-01-31|title=U.S. Census website}}</ref>\n|blank1_name              = [[Geographic Names Information System|GNIS]] feature ID\n|blank1_info              = 1362193<ref name=\"GR3\">{{cite web|url=http://geonames.usgs.gov|accessdate=2008-01-31|title=US Board on Geographic Names|publisher=[[United States Geological Survey]]|date=2007-10-25}}</ref>\n|website                  = \n|footnotes                = \n}}\n'''Marquez''' ({{IPAc-en|m|\u0251r|\u02c8|k|e\u026a}} {{respell|mar|KAY|'}}<ref>http://www.texastripper.com/pronounce/locations-m.html</ref>) is a city in [[Leon County, Texas|Leon County]], [[Texas]], United States. The population was 263 at the 2010 census.\n\n==Geography==\nMarquez is located at {{coord|31.240121|-96.255336|type:city_region:US|format=dms|display=inline}} (31.240121, -96.255336).<ref name=\"GR1\">{{cite web|url=https://www.census.gov/geographies/reference-files/time-series/geo/gazetteer-files.html|publisher=[[United States Census Bureau]]|accessdate=2011-04-23|date=2011-02-12|title=US Gazetteer files: 2010, 2000, and 1990}}</ref>\n\nAccording to the [[United States Census Bureau]], the city has a total area of {{convert|1.2|sqmi|km2}}, all of it land.\n\n==Demographics==\n{{US Census population\n|1940= 381\n|1950= 287\n|1960= 194\n|1970= 185\n|1980= 231\n|1990= 270\n|2000= 220\n|2010= 263\n|estyear=2016\n|estimate=268\n|estref=<ref name=\"USCensusEst2016\">{{cite web|url=https://www.census.gov/programs-surveys/popest/data/tables.2016.html|title=Population and Housing Unit Estimates|accessdate=June 9, 2017}}</ref>\n|footnote=U.S. Decennial Census<ref name=\"DecennialCensus\">{{cite web|url=https://www.census.gov/programs-surveys/decennial-census.html|title=Census of Population and Housing|publisher=Census.gov|accessdate=June 4, 2015}}</ref>\n}}\nAs of the [[census]]<ref name=\"GR2\" /> of 2000, there were 220 people, 90 households, and 59 families residing in the city. The [[population density]] was 183.3 people per square mile (70.8/km<sup>2</sup>). There were 113 housing units at an average density of 94.1/sq&nbsp;mi (36.4/km<sup>2</sup>). The racial makeup of the city was 81.82% [[White (U.S. Census)|White]], 8.64% [[African American (U.S. Census)|African American]], 1.36% [[Native American (U.S. Census)|Native American]], 8.18% from [[Race (United States Census)|other races]]. [[Hispanic (U.S. Census)|Hispanic]] or [[Latino (U.S. Census)|Latino]] of any race were 12.27% of the population.\n\nThere were 90 households out of which 31.1% had children under the age of 18 living with them, 52.2% were [[Marriage|married couples]] living together, 11.1% had a female householder with no husband present, and 34.4% were non-families. 33.3% of all households were made up of individuals and 20.0% had someone living alone who was 65 years of age or older. The average household size was 2.44 and the average family size was 3.14.\n\nIn the city, the population was spread out with 25.9% under the age of 18, 5.5% from 18 to 24, 25.5% from 25 to 44, 22.7% from 45 to 64, and 20.5% who were 65 years of age or older. The median age was 41 years. For every 100 females, there were 94.7 males. For every 100 females age 18 and over, there were 87.4 males.\n\nThe median income for a household in the city was $18,333, and the median income for a family was $34,375. Males had a median income of $29,286 versus $12,250 for females. The [[per capita income]] for the city was $14,122. About 27.9% of families and 29.1% of the population were below the [[poverty line]], including 34.1% of those under the age of eighteen and 22.7% of those sixty five or over.\n\n==Education==\nThe City of Marquez is served by the [[Leon Independent School District]].\n\n==References==\n<references />\n\n{{Leon County, Texas}}\n\n{{authority control}}\n\n[[Category:Cities in Texas]]\n[[Category:Cities in Leon County, Texas]]\n", "text_old": "{{Infobox settlement\n|official_name            = Marquez, Texas\n|settlement_type          = [[City]]\n|nickname                 = \n|motto                    =\n\n<!-- Images -->\n|image_skyline            = Post Office, Marquez, TX IMG_4441.JPG\n|imagesize                = 200px\n|image_caption            = Marquez Post Office\n|image_flag               = \n|image_seal               =\n\n<!-- Maps -->\n|image_map                = TXMap-doton-Marquez.PNG\n|mapsize                  = 250px\n|map_caption              = Location of Marquez, Texas\n|image_map1               = Leon County Marquez.svg\n|mapsize1                 = 250px\n|map_caption1             =\n\n<!-- Location -->\n|subdivision_type         = [[List of sovereign states|Country]]\n|subdivision_name         = United States\n|subdivision_type1        = [[U.S. state|State]]\n|subdivision_name1        = [[Texas]]\n|subdivision_type2        = [[List of counties in Texas|County]]\n|subdivision_name2        = [[Leon County, Texas|Leon]]\n\n<!-- Government -->\n|government_footnotes     = \n|government_type          = \n|leader_title             = \n|leader_name              = \n|leader_title1            = \n|leader_name1             = \n|established_title        = \n|established_date         =\n\n<!-- Area -->\n|unit_pref  =  Imperial\n|area_footnotes           = \n|area_magnitude           = \n|area_total_km2           = 3.1\n|area_land_km2            = 3.1\n|area_water_km2           = 0.0\n|area_total_sq_mi         