nited States Census Bureau]]|accessdate=2011-04-23|date=2011-02-12|title=US Gazetteer files: 2010, 2000, and 1990}}</ref>\n\nAccording to the [[United States Census Bureau]], the city has a total area of {{convert|1.2|sqmi|km2}}, all of it land.\n\n==Demographics==\n{{US Census population\n|1940= 381\n|1950= 287\n|1960= 194\n|1970= 185\n|1980= 231\n|1990= 270\n|2000= 220\n|2010= 263\n|estyear=2016\n|estimate=268\n|estref=<ref name=\"USCensusEst2016\">{{cite web|url=https://www.census.gov/programs-surveys/popest/data/tables.2016.html|title=Population and Housing Unit Estimates|accessdate=June 9, 2017}}</ref>\n|footnote=U.S. Decennial Census<ref name=\"DecennialCensus\">{{cite web|url=https://www.census.gov/programs-surveys/decennial-census.html|title=Census of Population and Housing|publisher=Census.gov|accessdate=June 4, 2015}}</ref>\n}}\nAs of the [[census]]<ref name=\"GR2\" /> of 2000, there were 220 people, 90 households, and 59 families residing in the city. The [[population density]] was 183.3 people per square mile (70.8/km<sup>2</sup>). There were 113 housing units at an average density of 94.1/sq&nbsp;mi (36.4/km<sup>2</sup>). The racial makeup of the city was 81.82% [[White (U.S. Census)|White]], 8.64% [[African American (U.S. Census)|African American]], 1.36% [[Native American (U.S. Census)|Native American]], 8.18% from [[Race (United States Census)|other races]]. [[Hispanic (U.S. Census)|Hispanic]] or [[Latino (U.S. Census)|Latino]] of any race were 12.27% of the population.\n\nThere were 90 households out of which 31.1% had children under the age of 18 living with them, 52.2% were [[Marriage|married couples]] living together, 11.1% had a female householder with no husband present, and 34.4% were non-families. 33.3% of all households were made up of individuals and 20.0% had someone living alone who was 65 years of age or older. The average household size was 2.44 and the average family size was 3.14.\n\nIn the city, the population was spread out with 25.9% under the age of 18, 5.5% from 18 to 24, 25.5% from 25 to 44, 22.7% from 45 to 64, and 20.5% who were 65 years of age or older. The median age was 41 years. For every 100 females, there were 94.7 males. For every 100 females age 18 and over, there were 87.4 males.\n\nThe median income for a household in the city was $18,333, and the median income for a family was $34,375. Males had a median income of $29,286 versus $12,250 for females. The [[per capita income]] for the city was $14,122. About 27.9% of families and 29.1% of the population were below the [[poverty line]], including 34.1% of those under the age of eighteen and 22.7% of those sixty five or over.\n\n==Education==\nThe City of Marquez is served by the [[Leon Independent School District]].\n\n==References==\n<references />\n\n{{Leon County, Texas}}\n\n{{authority control}}\n\n[[Category:Cities in Texas]]\n[[Category:Cities in Leon County, Texas]]\n", "name_user": "165.225.34.222", "label": "unsafe", "comment": "", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Marquez,_Texas"}
{"title_page": "Hakea fraseri", "text_new": "{{speciesbox\n|genus = Hakea\n|species = fraseri\n|authority = [[Robert Brown (Scottish botanist from Montrose)|R.Br.]]<ref name=\"APC\">{{cite web |title=''Hakea fraseri'' |url=https://biodiversity.org.au/nsl/services/apc-format/display/70179 |website=Australian Plant Census |accessdate=20 April 2020}}</ref>\n|\n|}}\n\n'''''Hakea fraseri''''', is a species of shrub or small tree commonly known as the '''corkwood oak''',<ref name=\"RBGS\">{{cite web |title=''Hakea fraseri'' |url=http://plantnet.rbgsyd.nsw.gov.au/cgi-bin/NSWfl.pl?page=nswfl&lvl=sp&name=Hakea~fraseri |website=PlantNET-Flora of NSW Online |publisher=Royal Botanic Gardens Sydney |accessdate=20 April 2020}}</ref> is a shrub in the family ''[[Proteaceae]]''  and is [[endemism|endemic]] to northern New South Wales. It has furrowed bark, pendulous foliage and creamy-white flowers in spring.\n\n==Description==\n''Hakea fraseri'' is a shrub or small tree growing to {{cvt|1-6|m}} high with multiple stems, dark grey rough bark and does not form a [[lignotuber]]. The branchlets are a whitish colour, covered with flattened, soft hairs, new shoots glossy rusty coloured hairs over glossy white hairs. The leaves are simple, varying length with a weeping habit, {{cvt|11-30|cm}} long {{cvt|0.9-1.4|mm}} wide, more or less smooth and ending with hook. The [[inflorescence]] consists of 25-50 cream-white flowers borne in leaf axils on a stalk {{cvt|9-25|mm}} long that is covered with reddish-brown, short, matted hairs over whitish flattened hairs. The [[pedicel (botany)|pedicel]] {{cvt|3.5-8|mm}} long, thickly covered with flattened hairs that extend onto the cream-white [[perianth]] when in bud, the [[pistil]]  {{cvt|17-26|mm}} long. The fruit is narrowly egg-shaped, {{cvt|30-40|mm}} long, {{cvt|11-17|mm}} wide and a long obscure beak. Flowering occurs in spring.<ref name=\"RBGS\"/><ref name=\"FOAB\">{{cite book |last1=Wilson (ed) |first1=Annette |last2=Barker |first2=Robyn M. |last3=Haegi |first3=Laurence A. |last4=Barker |first4=William R. |title=\"Flora of Australia\" |date=1999 |publisher=ABRS-Department of Environment & Heritage |location=Canberra/Melbourne |isbn=0-643-06454-0}}</ref>\n\n==Taxonomy and naming==\nThis species was first formally described in 1830 [[Robert Brown (Scottish botanist from Montrose)|Robert Brown]] and the description was published in ''[[Supplementum primum prodromi florae Novae Hollandiae]]''.<ref name=\"BHL\">{{cite web |title=Supplementum primum prodromi florae Novae Hollandiae |url=https://www.biodiversitylibrary.org/item/77294#page/540/mode/1up |website=Biodiversity Heritage Library |accessdate=21 April 2020}}</ref><ref name=\"APNI\">{{cite web |title=''Hakea fraseri'' |url=https://biodiversity.org.au/nsl/services/rest/instance/apni/480580 |website=Australian Plant Name Index |accessdate=21 April 2020}}</ref>The [[botanical name|specific epithet]] ''(fraseri)'' honours Charles Fraser the first colonial botanist and Superintendent of the New South Wales botanic gardens.<ref name=\"SAF\">{{cite web |title=''Hakea fraseri'' |url=http://www.flora.sa.gov.au/efsa/lucid/Hakea/key/Australian%20Hakea%20species/Media/Html/Hakea_fraseri.htm |website=Fact Sheet-Flora of South Australia |publisher=South Australian Government |accessdate=21 April 2020}}</ref>\n\n==Distribution and habitat==\nCorkwood oak  is a rare species in [[New South Wales]] confined to the New England Tablelands  below [[Wollomombi]], [[Dangar Falls|Dangar]], [[Tia Falls|Tia]] and [[Apsley Falls|Apsley]] Falls on steep slopes and vertical rock situations in gorges.<ref name=\"FOAB\"/> \n \n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n{{Taxonbar|from=Q18082590}}\n\n[[Category:Hakea|fraseri]]\n[[Category:Flora of New South Wales]]\n", "text_old": "{{speciesbox\n|genus = Hakea\n|species = fraseri\n|authority = [[Robert Brown (Scottish botanist from Montrose)|R.Br.]]<ref name=\"APC\">{{cite web |title=''Hakea fraseri'' |url=https://biodiversity.org.au/nsl/services/apc-format/display/70179 |website=Australian Plant Census |accessdate=20 April 2020}}</ref>\n|\n|}}\n\n'''''Hakea fraseri''''', is a species of shrub or small tree commonly known as the '''corkwood oak''',<ref name=\"RBGS\">{{cite web |title=''Hakea fraseri'' |url=http://plantnet.rbgsyd.nsw.gov.au/cgi-bin/NSWfl.pl?page=nswfl&lvl=sp&name=Hakea~fraseri |website=PlantNET-Flora of NSW Online |publisher=Royal Botanic Gardens Sydney |accessdate=20 April 2020}}</ref> is a shrub in the family ''[[Proteaceae]]''  and is [[endemism|endemic]] to northern New South Wales. It has furrowed bark, pendulous foliage and creamy-white flowers in spring.\n\n==Description==\n''Hakea fraseri'' is a shrub or small tree growing to {{cvt|1-6|m}} high with multiple stems, dark grey rough bark and does not form a [[lignotuber]]. The branchlets are a whitish colour, covered with flattened, soft hairs, new shoots glossy rusty coloured hairs over glossy white hairs. The leaves are simple, varying length with a weeping habit, {{cvt|11-30|cm}} long {{cvt|0.9-1.4|mm}} wide, more or less smooth and ending with hook. The [[inflorescence]] consists of 25-50 cream-white flowers borne in leaf axils on a stalk {{cvt|9-25|mm}} long that is covered with reddish-brown, short, matted hairs over whitish flattened hairs. The [[pedicel (botany)|pedicel]] {{cvt|3.5-8|mm}} long, thickly covered with flattened hairs that extend onto the cream-white [[perianth]] when in bud, the [[pistil]]  {{cvt|17-26|mm}} long. The fruit is narrowly egg-shaped, {{cvt|30-40|mm}} long, {{cvt|11-17|mm}} wide and a long obscure beak. Flowering occurs in spring.<ref name=\"RBGS\"/><ref name=\"FOAB\">{{cite book |last1=Wilson (ed) |first1=Annette |last2=Barker |first2=Robyn M. |last3=Haegi |first3=Laurence A. |last4=Barker |first4=William R. |title=\"Flora of Australia\" |date=1999 |publisher=ABRS-Department of Environment & Heritage |location=Canberra/Melbourne |isbn=0-643-06454-0}}</ref>\n\n==Taxonomy and naming==\nThis species was first formally described in 1830 [[Robert Brown (Scottish botanist from Montrose)|Robert Brown]] and the description was published in ''[[Supplementum primum prodromi florae Novae Hollandiae]]''.<ref name=\"BHL\">{{cite web |title=Supplementum primum prodromi florae Novae Hollandiae |url=https://www.biodiversitylibrary.org/item/77294#page/540/mode/1up |website=Biodiversity Heritage Library |accessdate=21 April 2020}}</ref><ref name=\"APNI\">{{cite web |title=''Hakea fraseri'' |url=https://biodiversity.org.au/nsl/services/rest/instance/apni/480580 |website=Australian Plant Name Index |accessdate=21 April 2020}}</ref>The [[botanical name|specific epithet]] ''(fraseri)'' honours Charles Fraser the first colonial botanist and Superintendent of the New South Wales botanic gardens.<ref name=\"SAF\">{{cite web |title=''Hakea fraseri'' |url=http://www.flora.sa.gov.au/efsa/lucid/Hakea/key/Australian%20Hakea%20species/Media/Html/Hakea_fraseri.htm |website=Fact Sheet-Flora of South Australia |publisher=South Australian Government |accessdate=21 April 2020}}</ref> \n \n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n{{Taxonbar|from=Q18082590}}\n\n[[Category:Hakea|fraseri]]\n[[Category:Flora of New South Wales]]\n", "name_user": "Allthingsnative", "label": "safe", "comment": "Add distribution and habitat", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Hakea_fraseri"}
{"title_page": "Tfue", "text_new": "\\\n| occupation           \n| residence            = [[Indian Rocks Beach, Florida]]\n| website              =\n| pseudonym            =\n| channel_name         = I do'ny know\n| associated_acts      = {{flatlist|\n*[[Ninja (streamer)|Ninja]]\n*Cloakzy\n*Symfuhny\n*72hrs\n*Nate Hill\n*Tennp0\n}}\n| module               = {{Infobox YouTube personality|\n| embed                = Yes\n| name                 = Tfue\n| channel_display_name = Tfue\n| channel_direct_url   = channel/UC9lSZSYpDDE18hoFA7YlBpw\n| years_active         = 2014\u2013present\n| genre                = {{hlist|[[Video game|Gaming]]|[[Vlog]]}}\n| subscribers          = 11.6 million\n| views                = 1.2 billion\n| associated_acts      = JOOGSQUAD PPJT\n| silver_button        = Yes\n| silver_year          = 2018\n| gold_button          = Yes\n| gold_year            = 2018\n| diamond_button       = Yes\n| diamond_year         = 2019\n| stats_update         = April 11, 2020\n}}\n}}\n'''Turner Ellis Tenney''' (born January 2, 1998),<ref name=FazeTfue>{{cite web|url=https://fazeclan.com/pages/tfue|title=FaZe Tfue|publisher=[[FaZe Clan]]|archive-url =https://web.archive.org/web/20190529050155/https://fazeclan.com/pages/tfue|archive-date = May 29, 2019|access-date=May 27, 2019}}</ref><ref name=BdayTweet>{{cite tweet|number=1080361518766600192|title=it's My 21st Birthday!!!|first=Turner|last=Tenney|authorlink=Tfue|user=TTfue|date=January 1, 2019|access-date=June 4, 2019}}</ref> better known by his online alias '''Tfue''', is an American [[Video game live streaming|live streamer]], [[YouTuber]], [[Esports|professional gamer]] and [[Internet celebrity|internet personality]].\n\n== Career ==\nTfue transitioned to ''[[Fortnite Battle Royale]]'' as it was quickly exploding in popularity. Tenney later joined [[FaZe Clan]], a professional esports organization, on April 30, 2018.<ref name=Dot /> \n\n== Personal life ==\nTenney is from [[Indian Rocks Beach, Florida]].\n\n== Controversies ==\nIn May, 2018 Tenney was banned from [[Twitch (service)|Twitch]] for 30 days after saying an alleged racial slur. Twitch reversed the ban after reviewing the word wasn't used in a racial manner.<ref name=\"Dot\">{{Cite web|url=https://dotesports.com/news/faze-tfue-banned-facts|title=Who is FaZe Tfue, and why was he banned from Twitch?|last=Valens|first=Ana|date=September 6, 2018|website=Dot Esports|publisher=[[The Daily Dot]]|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=May 27, 2019}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.newsweek.com/tfue-xqc-daequan-banned-why-twitch-epic-livestreamfails-fortnite-6ix9ine-991855|title=FaZe Tfue, TSM Daequan and XQC Banned: What Happened This Time? (UPDATE)|last=Asarch|first=Steven|date=June 22, 2018|website=[[Newsweek]]|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=May 27, 2019}}</ref>\n\nOn July 2, 2018 Tenney received a permanent account ban on his [[Epic Games]] accounts because he was selling and buying Epic Games accounts, which is prohibited by Epic Games' terms and conditions.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.dexerto.com/fortnite/epic-games-clarify-why-faze-clans-tfue-received-a-permanent-account-ban-105534|title=Epic Games Clarify Why FaZe Clan's TFUE Received a Permanent Account Ban|last=Kent|first=Mike|date=June 22, 2018|website=Dexerto|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=May 11, 2019}}</ref> A week later, Tenney was banned from Twitch again, this time for 14 days, for unknown reasons.<ref name=\"Dot\" />\n\nOn May 20, 2019, Tenney filed a lawsuit against [[FaZe Clan]], claiming they \"pressured Tenney to live in one of its homes in [[Los Angeles]], pressured him to underage drinking and illegally gambling. FaZe also continuously pressured and encouraged him to engage in dangerous stunts.\" Tenney also claimed, that \"he only got 20% from any branded videos that are published on Twitch, YouTube or social media and half of his revenue from touring and appearances.\"<ref>{{Cite magazine|last=Cullins|first=Ashley|date=May 20, 2019|title=Esports Pro Sues Gaming Organization FaZe Clan Over \"Oppressive\" Contract|url=https://www.hollywoodreporter.com/amp/thr-esq/tfue-sues-faze-clan-oppressive-contract-1212124|magazine=[[The Hollywood Reporter]]|page=|pages=|doi=|pmid=|access-date=May 27, 2019}}</ref> FaZe Clan responded on Twitter, saying they didn't take any money from his tournament winnings, Twitch and YouTube revenue and his social media. They also said that they \"took $60,000 from his branded videos\" and offered Tenney \"an improved contract multiple times, with 100% of the money going to Tenney, but he rejected or ignored all of them.\"<ref name=Newsweek2>{{cite magazine|url=https://www.newsweek.com/faze-tfue-contract-drama-fortnite-lawyer-blast-money-1434123|title=Tfue Contract Leak? FaZe Clan Streamer Responds to Organization|first=Steven|last=Asarch|magazine=[[Newsweek]]|date=May 23, 2019|access-date=May 27, 2019}}</ref>\n\nOn August 1, 2019, FaZe Clan filed a federal lawsuit in New York suing Tenney, claiming Tenney violated his contract by disparaging the company and trying to form a rival esports organization. The organization also claims that Tenney directly leaked confidential information about his contract to media publications, violating their terms.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.theverge.com/2019/8/1/20750678/faze-clan-tfue-lawsuit-20-million-streaming-earnings-rival-esports-team|title=Faze Clan sues Fortnite star Tfue, claims he earned more than $20 million from streaming|last=Alexander|first=Julia|date=August 1, 2019|website=[[The Verge]]|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=}}</ref>\n\nOn September 2, 2019, Tenney again said a racial slur while streaming, but Twitch did not ban Tenney.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://dotesports.com/streaming/news/tfue-allegedly-uses-racial-slur-on-stream|title=Tfue appears to say racial slur on stream|last=Stavropoulos|first=Andreas|date=September 3, 2019|website=Dot Esports|language=en-US|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=2019-12-16}}</ref> \n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:1998 births]]\n[[Category:American esports players]]\n[[Category:FaZe Clan players]]\n[[Category:Fortnite]]\n[[Category:People from Pinellas County, Florida]]\n[[Category:YouTube Diamond Play Button recipients]]\n[[Category:Twitch streamers]]\n", "text_old": "{{short description|American streamer and e-sports player}}\n{{use mdy dates|date=May 2019}}\n{{Infobox Twitch streamer\n| name                 = Tfue\n| logo                 = \n| logo_caption         = \n| image                = Tfue.jpg.png\n| caption              = Tfue in December 2018\n| birth_name           = Turner Ellis Tenney\n| birth_date           = {{birth date and age|1998|1|2}}<ref name=FazeTfue /><ref name=BdayTweet /> <!-- See talk before changing -->\n| birth_place          = [[Indian Rocks Beach, Florida]]\n| death_date           =\n| death_place          =\n| nationality          = American\n| occupation           = [[Live streamer]] \u2022 [[YouTuber]]\n| residence            = [[Indian Rocks Beach, Florida]]\n| website              =\n| pseudonym            =\n| channel_name         = Tfue\n| years_active         = 2014\u2013present\n| genre                = {{hlist|[[Esports]]|[[Video game|Gaming]]}}\n| games                = ''[[Fortnite Battle Royale]]'', ''[[H1Z1]]'' and other [[battle royale game]]s\n| teams                = [[FaZe Clan]]<br>[[Rogue (esports)|Rogue]]<br>[[Denial Esports]]\n| followers            = 7.9 million\n| follower_date        = \n| views                = 199.5 million\n| view_date            = \n| associated_acts      = {{flatlist|\n*[[Ninja (streamer)|Ninja]]\n*Cloakzy\n*Symfuhny\n*72hrs\n*Nate Hill\n*Tennp0\n}}\n| module               = {{Infobox YouTube personality|\n| embed                = Yes\n| name                 = Tfue\n| channel_display_name = Tfue\n| channel_direct_url   = channel/UC9lSZSYpDDE18hoFA7YlBpw\n| years_active         = 2014\u2013present\n| genre                = {{hlist|[[Video game|Gaming]]|[[Vlog]]}}\n| subscribers          = 11.6 million\n| views                = 1.2 billion\n| associated_acts      = JOOGSQUAD PPJT\n| silver_button        = Yes\n| silver_year          = 2018\n| gold_button          = Yes\n| gold_year            = 2018\n| diamond_button       = Yes\n| diamond_year         = 2019\n| stats_update         = April 11, 2020\n}}\n}}\n'''Turner Ellis Tenney''' (born January 2, 1998),<ref name=FazeTfue>{{cite web|url=https://fazeclan.com/pages/tfue|title=FaZe Tfue|publisher=[[FaZe Clan]]|archive-url =https://web.archive.org/web/20190529050155/https://fazeclan.com/pages/tfue|archive-date = May 29, 2019|access-date=May 27, 2019}}</ref><ref name=BdayTweet>{{cite tweet|number=1080361518766600192|title=it's My 21st Birthday!!!|first=Turner|last=Tenney|authorlink=Tfue|user=TTfue|date=January 1, 2019|access-date=June 4, 2019}}</ref> better known by his online alias '''Tfue''', is an American [[Video game live streaming|live streamer]], [[YouTuber]], [[Esports|professional gamer]] and [[Internet celebrity|internet personality]].\n\n== Career ==\nTfue transitioned to ''[[Fortnite Battle Royale]]'' as it was quickly exploding in popularity. Tenney later joined [[FaZe Clan]], a professional esports organization, on April 30, 2018.<ref name=Dot /> \n\n== Personal life ==\nTenney is from [[Indian Rocks Beach, Florida]].\n\n== Controversies ==\nIn May, 2018 Tenney was banned from [[Twitch (service)|Twitch]] for 30 days after saying an alleged racial slur. Twitch reversed the ban after reviewing the word wasn't used in a racial manner.<ref name=\"Dot\">{{Cite web|url=https://dotesports.com/news/faze-tfue-banned-facts|title=Who is FaZe Tfue, and why was he banned from Twitch?|last=Valens|first=Ana|date=September 6, 2018|website=Dot Esports|publisher=[[The Daily Dot]]|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=May 27, 2019}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.newsweek.com/tfue-xqc-daequan-banned-why-twitch-epic-livestreamfails-fortnite-6ix9ine-991855|title=FaZe Tfue, TSM Daequan and XQC Banned: What Happened This Time? (UPDATE)|last=Asarch|first=Steven|date=June 22, 2018|website=[[Newsweek]]|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=May 27, 2019}}</ref>\n\nOn July 2, 2018 Tenney received a permanent account ban on his [[Epic Games]] accounts because he was selling and buying Epic Games accounts, which is prohibited by Epic Games' terms and conditions.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.dexerto.com/fortnite/epic-games-clarify-why-faze-clans-tfue-received-a-permanent-account-ban-105534|title=Epic Games Clarify Why FaZe Clan's TFUE Received a Permanent Account Ban|last=Kent|first=Mike|date=June 22, 2018|website=Dexerto|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=May 11, 2019}}</ref> A week later, Tenney was banned from Twitch again, this time for 14 days, for unknown reasons.<ref name=\"Dot\" />\n\nOn May 20, 2019, Tenney filed a lawsuit against [[FaZe Clan]], claiming they \"pressured Tenney to live in one of its homes in [[Los Angeles]], pressured him to underage drinking and illegally gambling. FaZe also continuously pressured and encouraged him to engage in dangerous stunts.\" Tenney also claimed, that \"he only got 20% from any branded videos that are published on Twitch, YouTube or social media and half of his revenue from touring and appearances.\"<ref>{{Cite magazine|last=Cullins|first=Ashley|date=May 20, 2019|title=Esports Pro Sues Gaming Organization FaZe Clan Over \"Oppressive\" Contract|url=https://www.hollywoodreporter.com/amp/thr-esq/tfue-sues-faze-clan-oppressive-contract-1212124|magazine=[[The Hollywood Reporter]]|page=|pages=|doi=|pmid=|access-date=May 27, 2019}}</ref> FaZe Clan responded on Twitter, saying they didn't take any money from his tournament winnings, Twitch and YouTube revenue and his social media. They also said that they \"took $60,000 from his branded videos\" and offered Tenney \"an improved contract multiple times, with 100% of the money going to Tenney, but he rejected or ignored all of them.\"<ref name=Newsweek2>{{cite magazine|url=https://www.newsweek.com/faze-tfue-contract-drama-fortnite-lawyer-blast-money-1434123|title=Tfue Contract Leak? FaZe Clan Streamer Responds to Organization|first=Steven|last=Asarch|magazine=[[Newsweek]]|date=May 23, 2019|access-date=May 27, 2019}}</ref>\n\nOn August 1, 2019, FaZe Clan filed a federal lawsuit in New York suing Tenney, claiming Tenney violated his contract by disparaging the company and trying to form a rival esports organization. The organization also claims that Tenney directly leaked confidential information about his contract to media publications, violating their terms.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.theverge.com/2019/8/1/20750678/faze-clan-tfue-lawsuit-20-million-streaming-earnings-rival-esports-team|title=Faze Clan sues Fortnite star Tfue, claims he earned more than $20 million from streaming|last=Alexander|first=Julia|date=August 1, 2019|website=[[The Verge]]|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=}}</ref>\n\nOn September 2, 2019, Tenney again said a racial slur while streaming, but Twitch did not ban Tenney.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://dotesports.com/streaming/news/tfue-allegedly-uses-racial-slur-on-stream|title=Tfue appears to say racial slur on stream|last=Stavropoulos|first=Andreas|date=September 3, 2019|website=Dot Esports|language=en-US|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=2019-12-16}}</ref> \n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:1998 births]]\n[[Category:American esports players]]\n[[Category:FaZe Clan players]]\n[[Category:Fortnite]]\n[[Category:People from Pinellas County, Florida]]\n[[Category:YouTube Diamond Play Button recipients]]\n[[Category:Twitch streamers]]\n", "name_user": "122.169.80.212", "label": "vandal", "comment": "", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/